<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Not to Consider Cambodia's Membership Until </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Member nations of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have unanimously
agreed not to discuss Cambodia's membership until a new legitimate
government is formed in that country, Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Local television station Channel 9 Tuesday quoted Surin as
saying that Cambodia's general election in July has yet to be
transformed into political solidarity and the situation in the
country is far from stable.
</P>
<P>
Surin said Thailand had discussed with other ASEAN nations
about Cambodia's membership. They agreed that it is not the right
time to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ASEAN countries hoped that the new Cambodian
government can be formed smoothly and be recognized by the
Cambodian people as well as the international community, Surin
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, the Thai Foreign Ministry confirmed that
Cambodian Co-Prime Minister Hun Sen had submitted a letter to his
Thai counterpart Chuan Leekpai, requesting the latter to ask the
ASEAN foreign ministers who will meet in New York at the end of
this month to allow Cambodia's entry.
</P>
<P>
Back in July 1997, ASEAN had planned to include Cambodia, Laos
and Myanmar into the organization to realize its ambition of a
greater ASEAN of ten countries.
</P>
<P>
However, the issue of Cambodia's membership was shelved after
bloody clashes broke out between the two ruling parties of the
country in the same month.
</P>
<P>
General elections were held in Cambodia in July 26, 1998, in
which Hun Sen's People's Party won a comfortable victory.
</P>
<P>
Despite allegations by the opposition Funcipec and Sam Rainsy
parties of election frauds in some areas, the ASEAN has announced
its acceptance of the election results.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN now groups nine countries -- Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Hard Currency Reserves Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The hard currency reserves
of the Romanian National Bank stood at 2.306 billion U.S. dollars
by the end of August, 11.85 percent lower than in July.
</P>
<P>
The largest hard currency reserve in the central bank was
registered in July 1998, while the lowest was seen in August 1998,
according to a report issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Because of demands by foreign investors to have their capital
and profits repatriated as a result of the financial crisis in
Russia, the bank intervened in sales in the second half of August,
which contributed to a drain in the bank's hard currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
But Mugur Isarescu, the central bank's governor, said the
financial crisis in Russia will not seriously influence Romania's
currency. He further predicted that Romania's currency will only
depreciate by 1-2 percent monthly.
</P>
<P>
On August 31, the national currency unit, the leu, depreciated
by 2 percent compared to that of August 3, showing a higher
depreciation rate compared to the 0.76, 1.76 and 1.8 percent
depreciation rate registered in July, June and May this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
