<HEADLINE> Big Oil Field Found at Sea off Northwest Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A big offshore oil field has
been discovered 1,356 meters under the sea level in No. 17 Water
Region near the Cabinda enclave in the north, according to a
press release issued here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Angola National Oil Company announced in the release that
the Lirio I Well sunk in the Region has been pumping out an
estimated amount of 11,000 barrels of quality crude oil per day.
</P>
<P>
This is the second well found by Elf Exploration Angola, a
subsidiary of the French Elf Corporation.  On March 11 this
year, Elf Angola also sank a well capable of putting out 12,000
barrels of oil per day in No. 17 Water Region near Luanda.
</P>
<P>
The company will soon make further exploration to identify the
actual oil reserves in the area.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the biggest oil producers in Africa, turning
out 750,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, a series of rich oil fields have been found
in the waters of northwestern Angola with a total identified
reserve of over five billion barrels. But currently, foreign oil
exploration companies such as AMOCO, EXXO, and Mobil are drilling
in these waters on lease.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has planned to greatly increase its oil
output, aiming to produce one million barrels per day by 2000 and
1.3 million barrels per day by 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
