<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders Call for End to Congo (K) Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of countries relevant
to the armed conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
have signed a joint communique in Zimbabwe Tuesday urging a
cease-fire to the five-week long armed conflict there.
</P>
<P>
The communique, reached by leaders of Rwanda, Uganda,
Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia, Zambia and Congo (K) was read out by
Secretary-General of the Organization of African Unity Salim
Ahmed Salim, Radio Uganda reported Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
It calls for end to hostility and an immediate cease-fire
between the two warring factions, urging withdrawal of foreign
troops from the war-stricken country.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of the Tutsi rebels in Congo are said to
have left before the signing of the communique and they claimed
that the communique is not binding for them, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The document also said defense ministers of the above
countries will continue to discuss the withdrawal of foreign
troops from Congo, Africa's third largest country in Ethiopia on
September 10.
</P>
<P>
Congolese President Laurent Kabila has accused Rwanda and
Uganda of sending troops to back rebels in his country, but both
countries denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
With the escalating of the conflict, Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia sent troops to Congo to help embattled Kabila in
mid-August, turning the tide of war against the rebels since.
</P>
<P>
This summit was called by Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
at the summit meeting of the Non-Alignment Movement held in
Durban, South Africa last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
