<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Prime Minister Accuses Syria of Hostility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz Tuesday blasted Syria for its hostility
towards Turkey by supporting the anti-Turkish Kurdish separatists.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who speaks hostility in the region with hostile
attitudes should focus on the policies of the Syrian government
that encourages separatist terrorism in the region," he said in
the West Bank city after meeting with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's remarks came in response to claims by Syrian
newspapers that Turkey's military alliance with Israel was
bringing more tensions to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Turkey have been at odds over sovereignty issues,
water rights, and the alleged Syrian support for Kurdish rebels
fighting for independence in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Syria fears that the growing military cooperation between
Israel and Turkey could leave it encircled by an enemy coalition.
</P>
<P>
Trying to reassure its skeptical neighbors, Yilmaz has
reiterated during his visits to Jordan and Israel which preceded
his visit to Ramallah that his country's military ties with
Israel would not pose a threat to any other country.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Israel have been developing strategic ties since
early 1996 when they signed a defense cooperation deal.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has allowed Israeli pilots to use its air space for
training, and Israel has been upgrading Turkish fighter planes
with its advanced technologies. The two sides have also conducted
joint naval maneuvers in the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Speaking earlier in Jerusalem Monday after his talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Yilmaz brushed aside
Syria's criticism of his Israeli visit.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly, I don't care how Syria comments on my visit (to
Israel). Everyone is aware of the hostile intentions of Syria
towards Turkey," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish leader confirmed Tuesday that Turkey and Israel
plan to conduct joint naval maneuvers in November this year. The
two sides held their first joint naval exercise in January.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli daily Haaretz quoted security sources as saying
Tuesday that Egypt and Jordan have been invited to join the
Israeli-Turkish exercises, but Yilmaz refused to confirm this.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Turkey's position on the Israeli-Palestinian
negotiations, Yilmaz urged Israel to accept a U.S. plan that
calls for a 13.1 percent Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank
in exchange for Palestinian measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides must take constructive steps to get this peace
process out of the freeze it is in," he said.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has already accepted the U.S. plan but Israel said it
would endorse it only on condition that 3 percent of the land be
designated as a nature reserve, where Israel retains full security
control.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said Turkey and the PNA have signed cooperation
agreements in the fields of culture, education and the
environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
