<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Rejects Annan's Reference to Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 8 (Xinhua) -- India Tuesday rejected
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan's reference to Jammu
and Kashmir, asserting that there was no increase in tension with
its arch-rival Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his annual report on the eve of the U.N. General
Assembly session, said, "The rising tension between India and
Pakistan over Kashmir and other issues is also a major cause of
concern."
</P>
<P>
Sharply reacting to the reference, a spokesman of India's
External Affairs Ministry said that "there is no increase in
tension" between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman termed Annan's report as a "routine feature"
which is submitted every year to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"References to the Jammu and Kashmir have been included in the
U.N. Secretary General's report since 1993," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the U.N.'s work last year, Annan also clubbed the
Kashmir issue with the deadlocked peace process in Cyprus, the
turmoil in Afghanistan and the stalemate in the Middle East peace
process, and listed the issue as one of the causes of concern
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The Indian foreign ministry spokesman said that both India and
Pakistan had arrived at an understanding on how to start their
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"The process is expected to be resumed after final instructions
are given by the prime ministers of India and Pakistan at their
meeting in New York on September 23," he said.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and his Pakistani
counterpart Nawaz Sharif met for the first time in Sri Lanka at
the end of July which produced little results as both sides blamed
each other for the continued standoff.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled meeting between the two leaders during the recent
summit of the Non-Aligned Movement in South Africa was canceled at
the last minute because of "pressing engagements" at home of the
Pakistani leader.
</P>
<P>
There is no sign of softening of positions on Kashmir from both
India and Pakistan with New Delhi rejecting any third party
involvement in resolving the dispute while Islamabad wants an
internationally supervised referendum to determine whether the
region should be folded into India or the latter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
