<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Convicts Appeal Against Death Sentence in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen people condemned to
death in Sierra Leone last month have appealed against their
sentences and waited for hearings of their cases at the Appeal
Court, Justice Minister Solomon Berewa said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said the 16 civilians including five
journalists were found guilty on August 25 of collaborating with
the army junta which overthrew President Ahmad Fejan Kabbah for
10 months.
</P>
<P>
Among those condemned to death are former junta spokesman
Allieu Kamara, junta's Central Bank Governor Christian Kargbo,
former Director-General of the Sierra Leone Broadcasting
Corporation and a female broadcaster who gave birth to a baby in
prison in July.
</P>
<P>
Under Sierra Leonian law, the convicts have 21 days to appeal
against their sentences and if the Appeal Court fails to hear the
cases, they can turn to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Failure there would force them to throw themselves on the
mercy of a special committee and ultimately the president of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Since President Kabbah resumed office last March from exile in
Guinea, a total of 60 civilians and 38 junta soldiers were put on
trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
