<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nazarbayev Rules out Severe Impact of Russia's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan's President
Nursultan Nazarbayev said on Tuesday that the current Russian
financial turmoil will have no severe impact on his nation's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in the presidential residence,
Nazarbayev attributed his conclusion to the separation of the two
nations' financial systems five year ago.
</P>
<P>
The president's remarks came after the downturn of Kazakhstan's
currency tenge against the U.S. dollar amid rising prices since
the end of August.
</P>
<P>
In the recent week the exchange rate in the capital city
plunged from 78.5 to 81 tenges to a dollar. The rate in some areas
outside Alma-Ata was 100-1. As a result, Kazakhstan's banks and
residents were reportedly rushing to buy the hard greenback.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev called on nationals to keep calm in the face of the
Russia's economic chaos, which has already triggered a political
crisis in Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
