<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Raps Israeli-Turkish Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
Tuesday accused Turkey and Israel of attempting to besiege the
Middle East militarily and politically under the auspices of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries are trying to lay a siege in order to block
the region, Syria and Lebanese people's resistance movement,"
Hrawi said when meeting with representatives of a Lebanese
non-governmental party.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Arab people must be aware and keep alert
against this manoeuvre as they did in the past.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi highly praised Lebanon's anti-Israeli resistance
movement, saying that it is aimed at restoring Lebanon's land and
its legitimate right.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi's comments came as Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz
is visiting Israel as part of his regional tour that also includes
Jordan and the Palestinian self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the West Bank city Ramallah after meeting
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Tuesday, Yilmaz refuted the
Syrian criticism of his visit to Israel. He has reiterated that
Turkey's cooperation with Israel does not threaten any third party.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been enhancing its military cooperation
with Israel since early 1996 when they signed a defense
cooperation agreement.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is allowing Israeli pilots to use its airspace for
training, and Israel in turn has been upgrading Turkey's F-4
fighter planes under a contract worth 630 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israel's growing military cooperation with Turkey and Jordan
has sparked harsh criticism and fears from most Arab countries,
especially Syria and Lebanon. Israel is occupying the Golan
Heights of Syria and a buffer zone in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its closes ally Syria feared that Israel, Jordan
and turkey could form a military alliance, which could threaten
the security and interests of other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's resistance movement has been waging an anti-Israeli
guerrilla war in the 1,200-square-kilometer South Lebanon Security
Zone occupied by Israel in 1985 to allegedly protect its north from
Lebanese guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
