<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-08 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Syria to Forge Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Syria are planning a
bilateral free trade zone as a contribution to the regional
efforts towards the establishment of an Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
Joint Technical committees of Egypt and Syria are drafting an
agreement on the free trade zone, the Middle East News Agency
(MENA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which is scheduled to be initialed in
Damascus by the end of this year, tariffs will be phased out in
five years, the MENA quoted an official of Egyptian embassy in
Syria as saying.
</P>
<P>
Trade Secretary at the embassy Abdel Abdel Aziz said that the
two countries now have trade ties in transport, tourism,
communications and information.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume reached 240 million pounds (70.6 million U.S.
dollars) in 1996 from 94 million pounds (27.7 million dollars) in
1991.
</P>
<P>
As a prelude to an Arab common market, which is planned to take
shape by 2007, moves for the establishment of bilateral free trade
areas have started among Arab states since the beginning of this
year.
</P>
<P>
So far, Egypt has forged free trade agreements with Morocco and
Tunisia, and will clinch similar deals with Jordan, Kuwait,
Bahrain Saudi Arabia and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon have agreed to cut down customs by 25 percent
annually starting next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Dissatisfied on TRASECA Cost-Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Russia Tuesday criticized the
TRASECA project with regard to its cost-efficiency at the
international conference in Baku on establishing a transportation
corridor between Europe, the Caucasus and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency quoted the head of the Russian
delegation Yevgeny Kazantsev as saying that given equal
conditions, transportation tariffs via Russia are 1.7 times lower
for grain, cotton and containers and 1.2 times lower for oil and
non-ferrous metals than via TRASECA routes.
</P>
<P>
Kazantsev, the Deputy Transportation Minister, noted that the
project are hindered by large investments into transportation
infrastructure, additional costs of two railroad-ferry links
through the Caspian and Black seas, hidden mountain passes and
technically dangerous zones through the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official pointed out that TRASECA should be linked
to the existing Central Asian-Siberian and Trans-Siberian
railroads to provide better terms for shipping cargo between
Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia cannot join the basic multilateral
agreement on TRASECA. Most participants in the project have signed
multilateral and bilateral agreement with Russia.
</P>
<P>
The agreements should be coordinated with regard to "previous
decisions adopted within the framework of numerous international
organizations", he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has designed an oil transportation project passing via
Chechnya and the Black Sea port of Novorossiisk, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
