<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Savings Spur Czech Real Estate Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 8 (Xinhua) -- One out of five Czech residents
have joined a housing savings account program by the end of July
this year, greatly boosting the nation's real estate industry.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of savings under the program registered a
record high of 70 billion Koruny (2.26 billion U.S. dollars) by
the end of July, said a report of the bank in charge of the
program.
</P>
<P>
The program is an important measure by the Czech government
to raise more money to facilitate the building of new houses.
</P>
<P>
Czech residents can open a special account in a designated bank
with an amount ranging from 10,000 and to 1.5 million Koruny
(323-48,387 dollars). The shortest deposit period is five years
and the interest rate 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the program are entitled to use
governmental low-interest loan to purchase real estate when their
deposits reach a certain amount.
</P>
<P>
The government has so far granted loans worth 850 billion
Koruny (11.39 billion dollars) under the program, which has led to
a fast growth of real estate industry of the country.
</P>
<P>
The number of housing starts in the first quarter of this year
reached 7,760 units, up 35.1 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The number of housing starts increased to 4-5 units per
thousand residents, roughly the average level of the EU states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
