<HEADLINE> Museveni Back Home From Summit on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has returned home Tuesday afternoon from Victoria Falls,
Zimbabwe, where he has attended a regional summit on the armed
conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Museveni, who was accompanied by the Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim, was
received by Vice President Specioza Kazibwe and other senior
officials, a press release from the President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the two-day summit meeting, leaders of seven
countries in central and eastern Africa signed a joint communique
calling for end to hostilities and cessation of armed conflict in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
The leaders reaffirmed their support for unity, stability and
territorial integrity of Congo in accordance with the relevant
provisions of the OAU and the United Nations charters, including
provisions of a resolution adopted in Cairo in 1964 on territorial
integrity and the inviolability of national boundaries.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on the need to address the security concerns
of Congo and those of its neighbors. They say they are ready to
help in whatever ways possible to achieve this objective.
</P>
<P>
Another report here said the rebels fighting to oust President
Laurent Kabila refused to honor this document and vowed to fight
on unless Kabila ordered his armies to stop fighting. 
</P>
