<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Optimistic About Success of Ross' Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Middle
East peace envoy Miguel Moratinos expressed optimism Tuesday about
the success of the upcoming visit to the region by his
U.S. counterpart Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Israel Radio, Moratinos said his
optimism was based on the assessment that both Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) are committed to making
substantial progress in their talks over clinching an overdue deal
on Israel's next troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy made the remarks after a low-profile two-day
visit to the region. He had held talks with PNA President Yasser
Arafat, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Uzi Arad,
senior adviser to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes Ross will help Israel and the Palestinians
achieve a breakthrough in their negotiations over the second
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross is due in the region Wednesday for talks with Arafat and
Netanyahu in an effort to narrow their gaps over a U.S. proposal
calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullback in exchange for the
PNA's tougher measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said he had phoned Ross, who also voiced optimistic
over his upcoming visit.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of Ross' visit, Netanyahu convened his Inner Cabinet
Tuesday to discuss the issue of the redeployment. No details of
the discussions were released.
</P>
<P>
Ross was dispatched to region by U.S. President Bill Clinton
last week amid reports that Israel and the Palestinian side was
closer to clinching a deal on the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In a positive sign, Israeli, Palestinian and U.S. security
officials will meet Tuesday night in Tel Aviv to review a
memorandum of understanding on security cooperation worked out by
the three sides in last December.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians signed the memorandum but
Netanyahu refused to approve it, saying it was not detailed
enough to be effective.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos also said that it was possible that a tripartite
summit will be held by Netanyahu, Arafat and Clinton later this
month when they are in New York to attend the General Assembly of
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely speculated that Ross will try to arrange
such a summit to be held on September 23 in the White House to
celebrate the fifth anniversary of the historical signing of the
Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
For the past years, the EU has been trying to play a bigger
role in the Middle East peace process which is dominated by the
U.S. as the leading mediator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
