<HEADLINE> Privatization to Continue in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan parliament has
endorsed the continuation of the controversial privatization
process Tuesday after more than two weeks of hot debate.
</P>
<P>
The select committee reported to the House that it agreed with
the Ministry of Finance, Planning and Economic Development in
continuing the process, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that public enterprises whose privatization had
not ended should be finalized and those which were in earlier
stages will be subject to discussion between the minister and the
committee.
</P>
<P>
This agreement means the committee will proceed with the
privatization process with a right to examine the procedure.
</P>
<P>
A motion was moved two weeks ago over the suspension of the
privatization process due to alleged rampant corruption of
government officials in the process.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the privatization process should continue
while it is checked and examined at the same time while some
parliament members advocate immediate suspension of the process.
</P>
