<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Put Special Emphasis on Educating Women, Girls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday said that the 185-member
world body "will continue to place special emphasis" on the
education for women and girls all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The statement was contained in Annan's message marking the
International Literacy Day, which falls on September 8 every year.
</P>
<P>
"Recent years have seen significant gains in literacy rates,
school enrollment and spending on education. Yet, the twin goals
of universal literacy and equal access to education remain unmet,"
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
More than 960 million adults, two thirds of whom are women, are
illiterate, he said, adding that some 130 million children in
developing countries, two thirds of them girls, do not attend
primary school.
</P>
<P>
"In a fast-changing world, in rich and poor countries alike,
literacy demands continue to grow," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us remember that investments in literacy and education are
investments in health, in the environment, in labor, in the
development of human resources," he said. "Such investments can
yield the best of all returns: rewarding, prosperous lives for all
the world's people."
</P>
<P>
Almost all of the illiterate women live in the rural areas of
developing nations, particularly in Africa, the Arab countries and
East and South Asia, where the illiteracy rate for women is more
than 60 percent, according to Federico Mayor, the director-general
of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Literacy, in the broad sense, is the foundation for life
skills, ranging from basic oral and written communication to the
ability to solve scientific and social problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
