<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Warns to Use Any Means to Release Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi on Tuesday warned that Tehran will resort to any means to
seek release of Iranian diplomats and other citizens allegedly
kidnaped by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi issued the warning to the Taliban at a joint press
conference with his Armenian and Greek counterparts at the end of
the second tripartite meeting of the three countries on trilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the possibility that Tehran would use
force against the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the Taliban, before feeling too late, could offer a
satisfactory answer to Iran's demand on the release of Iranian
diplomats and other citizens," the Iranian foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) launched a
ground-breaking military drill on the Afghanistan border last
week and deployed the 70,000 troops and equipment involving in the
maneuvers in the border area.
</P>
<P>
Rumors widely spread here even said that Afghan refugees in
Iran would be armed to fight against the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi stressed that the Taliban should accept full
responsibility for the fate of Iranian hostages and should solve
the issue as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reports on the possible death of Iranian
diplomats, he said that a fact-finding team with the
participation of Iranian officials would be sent to Afghanistan
in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
He said that United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan would
make decision in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the missing 11 Iranian diplomats
and a reporter of the official news agency IRNA were killed on
August 8 in the Iranian consulate in Mazari Sharif in northern
Afghanistan when the Taliban forces occupied the city.
</P>
<P>
However, Tehran believes that the missing Iranian diplomats and
reporter are still safe at the hands of the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also said that Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
will come to Tehran next week to discuss ways to put an end to
the Afghan crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
