<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Raise Efficiency in Judiciary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambia should raise the
efficiency in judiciary so as to improve the delivery of justice
in the country, a senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of a workshop on alternative
dispute resolution, Zambian Legal Affairs Minister Vincent
Malambo revealed that the Zambian government spent a lot of money
because cases took too long to be disposed of in the Zambian
courts, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the inefficiency to the fact that Zambia's
Arbitration Act which had been in existence for several decades
had not been implemented in the country to date.
</P>
<P>
Malambo said the government would fully support efforts aimed
at creating efficiency in the delivery of justice in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of commercial justice should compliment rather
than hinder the wheels of commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same function, Arlene Render, the U.S. ambassador to
Zambia, said the United States was working closely with the
Zambian government to establish an alternative mechanism for
resolving disputes.
</P>
<P>
She explained that the alternative dispute resolution would
not replace courts but only help to improve the administration of
justice in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Render added that the alternative dispute resolution mechanism
would provide a means for settling civil disputes timely and
allow the scarce resources to be spent on complex criminal
matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
