<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Calls for Dialogue in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Tuesday called on all Cambodian
leaders to resolve their differences through dialogue, and to
exercise utmost restraint in a bid to avert any further outbreak
of violence.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, spokesman for the U.N. chief, said in a statement
read to reporters here that Annan is following very closely and
with deep concern the developments in Cambodia, in particular the
weekend's events.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general has written on September 2 to Cambodian
leaders Hun Sen and Ung Huot, as well as to Prince Ranariddh and
Sam Rainsy, strongly urging all Cambodian leaders to "exercise
utmost restraint so as to prevent any further outbreak of
violence," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general, through Mr. Lakhan Mehrotra, his
personal representative in Cambodia, remains ready to assist
Cambodia in finding a solution acceptable to all and consistent
with democratic practice," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's post-election standoff erupted into turmoil and
gunfire on Monday as the nation's second prime minister, Hun Sen,
ordered the arrest of his opponents and as security forces fired
into crowd of protesters, killing at least one person, according
to reports reaching here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation was touched off when three hand grenades were
thrown at Hun Sen's residence in the downtown area of Phnom Penh,
Cambodian capital.
</P>
<P>
After the outbreak of the latest confrontation, Sam Rainsy, a
candidate for the July 26 election, took refuge at the office of
the United Nations representative in Cambodia. Prince Ranariddh
and Sam Rainsy, who said irregularities marred the polls, has led
an increasingly assertive protest against the results of the
election, in which Hun Sen was declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general regrets the loss of life in these
events," the spokesman added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
