<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Little Hope for Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said there is "little hope" of an agreement between Israel
and the Palestinians on Israel's long-delayed troop withdrawal
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace process has been stalled for 18
months, though signs of some movements emerged last week when
U.S. President Bill Clinton telephoned Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross will fly to the
region Wednesday to push both leaders to reach agreement on a
U.S. initiative of another 13 percent West Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"If we judge according to what we listen and read, the hope for
an equitable and just peace would be little," Moussa told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He added that, however, "we should wait and see how the
situation would be like after Ross' arrival."
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Israeli and Palestinian leaders gave
differing accounts of the outcomes of their contacts and blamed
each other for the gaps that remained.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said there are many proposals but they are "not all
reasonable or logical." So far, he added, the Palestinian and
Israeli sides have not reached any definite formula on the
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is sending his envoys to Cairo to brief President
Hosni Mubarak on the Israeli stance on the possibility of reaching
an agreement with the Palestinians on the Israeli redeployment
plans, said Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Asked on whether the envoy's visit is meant to break the
stalemate in the Egyptian-Israeli relations, Moussa noted that
relations between the two countries are contingent on the
progress achieved on peace tracks.
</P>
<P>
"In case the peace process moved in an equitable balanced way
and a just agreement was reached, some parts of the current
stalemate in Egyptian-Israeli relations could be tackled," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to have diplomatic ties with
the Jewish state, but the relationship has turned cool since
Netanyahu's election two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
