<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Vows to Stablize Economy, Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabian second
Deputy Prime Minister Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz said Tuesday that
Saudi leaders were keen on safeguarding its economy and its
currency, the Saudi Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during a visit to the central region of
Al-Qaseem, Prince Sultan, who is also Defense and Aviation
Minister, said Saudi leaders were "taking action to protect the
economy from jitters or a meltdown."
</P>
<P>
"We are all seeking with steady and sound steps not to harm the
image of Saudi Arabia, the economy, exports and currency," Sultan
said.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government, in response to some rumors, announced on
August 31 that it had no intention to devaluate the Saudi currency
Riyal.
</P>
<P>
The rumors about Riyal's devaluation caused a panic on the
stock market prompting many dealers to sell their stocks for
U.S. dollars. But the market quickly restored stability as a
result of the confidence in the Saudi Riyal.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi currency has been under pressure as a result of
the sharp decline of oil prices in the world market since
last winter.
</P>
<P>
Although heavily hit by a sagging global oil market, the
oil-dependent Saudi economy has been growing steadily in the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
Saudi economy grew by 8.6 percent and 6 percent in 1996 and
1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The economy was boosted by the more active involvement of
private sector in local projects, higher government spending and
improvement in the overall financial situation.
</P>
<P>
However, structural economic problems, notably the double digit
unemployment, the economy's full dependency on the oil and the
state's hesitation to remove subsidies, have caused deep concerns
about the economy's instability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
