<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Congo Truce Hangs in the Air (by Shang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The prospect of a
cease-fire in the war-torn Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
remains unclear Tuesday after Congolese rebels rejected outright
a truce accord thrashed out by heads of state in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-led rebels said they would not observe the agreement
on a provisional cease-fire and the withdrawal of foreign troops
which was hammered out by all the six governments embroiled in
the Congo conflict at a summit at Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Because we were excluded (from the talks) we are not bound by
it," said rebel leader Bizima Karaha, former Congolese foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to fight on, saying the DRC and its allies "will only
know we exist when we start shooting".
</P>
<P>
After intensive behind-the-door talks which went into Monday
night, a cease-fire deal was finally struck by the DRC and its
allies, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia on the one side, and Uganda
and Rwanda, who reportedly backed the rebels, on the other.
</P>
<P>
DRC President Laurent Kabila accused Rwanda and Uganda of
invading his country by supporting the rebels, which the latter
two firmly denied.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, who chaired the summit,
said at a press conference Tuesday that the agreement would have
to be signed by the governments involved before it came into
effect.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a cease-fire so we can slowly but surely bring
peace to that country," Chiluba said, adding that all the
participants recognized Kabila as the DRC's legitimate ruler.
</P>
<P>
He said the cease-fire could only begin after defense
ministers from the six protagonists and Zambia meet later to draw
up a plan on the implementation of the deal.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers will meet at the OAU headquarters in
Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, on Thursday to explore cease-fire options.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the pact included the identification of all the
forces involved and an exchange of prisoners of war. The
possibility of a regional peacekeeping force would also be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that the African countries were
considering asking the United Unions to help monitor the
cease-fire because the exercise was too costly for Africa.
</P>
<P>
Contradictory to Congolese rebels' claim that they were not
consulted on the agreement, Chiluba said the rebels had agreed to
a cease-fire after a one-hour meeting with him and Organization
of African Unity Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim.
</P>
<P>
"They (the rebels) gave us a pledge voluntarily they were
going to respect the cease-fire. I hope they adhere to their own
word. If they refuse, it is pretty sad," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group, apparently angry at the isolation treatment
by Kabila and his three allies at the summit, left the summit
venue Tuesday about half an hour before the announcement of the
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Kabila had refused to meet face to face
with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no cease-fire before Kabila negotiates with us
directly," a rebel delegate said.
</P>
<P>
Rebel delegates were not allowed to address the meeting and
Karaha was only allowed to speak a few words at Tuesday's news
conference before he was whisked off to the airport. Chiluba said
it was because "they are not heads of state".
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Zimbabwean officials kept the eight-member rebel
delegation waiting for at least 90 minutes at the airport. When
they reached the conference venue later, they waited several more
hours while heads of state met in private.
</P>
<P>
Presidents at the summit emphasized the achievement of the
meeting, which has seen the biggest step yet taken towards
solving the crisis in the DRC. But they admitted that it was, as
always, difficult to implement cease-fire arrangements.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which did not attend the summit for reported
fears of offending Kabila and Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe,
quickly welcomed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela hailed the deal as a
"tribute to the high quality of leadership which Africa has
produced".
</P>
<P>
South Africa has been insisting on a diplomatic solution of
the Congo crisis and has clashed with Zimbabwe over the latter's
military intervention in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a extensive regional bloodshed have been raised after
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia sent their troops to the DRC on
August 20 to prop up Kabila's embattled troops. The Banyamulenge
rebels now control large areas in the eastern part of the central
African country.
</P>
<P>
As the war continued unabated in the DRC, the hope to end the
five-week conflict hangs on further peace efforts by the region.
</P>
<P>
The efforts would start with Thursday's meeting of defense
ministers of the involved countries in Ethiopia, followed by a
summit of Southern African Development Community (SADC) heads of
state this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit in Mauritius is seen as a good opportunity for
a high-level discussion of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela said Tuesday that the summit of the
14-nation bloc would be "solely concerned with setting up a
mechanism" to ensure the cease-fire.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
