<HEADLINE> Turkey Weakens 40 Percent of Rebels' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has weakened 40 percent
of the strength of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), a
senior Turkish official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Governor of the State of Emergency Region
Aydin Arslan, Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Arslan as saying that since the Turkish
government declared the state of emergency in the region in 1987,
21,333 PKK militants were killed in 16,843 incidents, while 4,696
civilians and 4,303 soldiers also lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the unlaterally-declared ceasefire by PKK leader
Abdullah Ocalan on August 28, Arslan said that the PKK needs time
to reorganize and rearm itself.
</P>
<P>
The PKK, set up in April 1979, was declared illegal following
the 1980 military coup. It has staged armed struggle for
independence in southeastern Turkey since August 1984, while the
government troops launch frequent attacks on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
