Palestinian-Israel peace talks achieve a just, comprehensive and
durable result that will secure the rights of all parties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, Abbas asked Jordan to continue its efforts to
remove the obstacles facing the peace process and "guarantee
Israel's implementation" of a U.S. proposal on Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has proposed Israel withdraw from an addition 13.1
percent of the West Bank in the second troop redeployment. The PNA
has accepted the proposal, but Israel first rejected it citing
security reasons then accepted it on condition that 3 percent of
the proposed land be turned into a nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
Abbas' Jordan visit came just ahead of the return to the region
by U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross, who is expected to arrive in
Israel on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There are mixed signals about the possible result of the Ross'
mission. Many predicted a breakthrough on brokering a deal on the
Israeli redeployment, while others doubted if Ross could achieve
it due to Washington's reluctance to exert further pressure on
Israel to soften its intransigence. 
</P>
