<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Udovenko on Intractable Blocks in Reforming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The working group on
reforming the Security Council of the United Nations has failed to
achieve substantive progresses, Hennadiy Udovenko, President of
the General Assembly, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the concluding session of the 52nd session of the
General Assembly, the outgoing President Udovenko said the working
group held 65 lengthy meetings in the past year, but it was once
again unable to submit any agreed recommendations on any of the
substantive issues related to Security Council reform.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko said while progress had been made in some areas, a
number of major stumbling blocks prevented the group from
fulfilling its mandate.
</P>
<P>
The President said among the most intractable ones is the
problem of finding a magic number that would increase the
representative character of the Council without impairing its
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
He said beyond the question of the total size of an enlarged
Council, controversy is still brewing around the creation of new
permanent seats and rotational arrangements to fill those seats,
the highly charged problem of the veto right with respect to both
current and prospective permanent members.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko said the reform of the Security Council is probably
one of the most difficult issues faced by the United Nations in
its history, any reform of the United Nations would be incomplete
without the reform of its main organ responsible for the
maintenance of international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko recommended to continue consultation on the matter
during the 53d session of GA and called on Member States to build
mutual trust and to move beyond marrow positions so as to reach a
common goal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
