<HEADLINE> Rwandan Refugees in DRC Flee into Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Thirty Rwandan refugees
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have arrived in west
Tanzania's Kigoma Region after rebels took arms to fight against
President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, of Hutu origin, have taken shelter in three
camps in the DRC since 1994, according to a report by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They told Kigoma authorities that a number of their
compatriots are still stranded at Fizi area waiting for an
opportunity to cross the Lake Tanganyika to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan refugees claimed to come from Kajembo, Runingo and
Kagunga camps in the DRC's Uvira Region on the western shore of
the lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian Ministry of Home Affairs have been informed of
the group's arrival and arrangements have been made to transport
them to Mbumba reception center in Ngara district of the
northwestern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
