<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Good Governance in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Secretary General Kofi Annan Tuesday said African countries
affected by conflicts should create a positive environment for
investment by adopting good governance and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
In his annual report released Tuesday, Annan notes that in
view of the continuing negative impact of external debt on many
developing countries, the international community should convert
into grants all remaining bilateral official debt for the poorest
countries.
</P>
<P>
He also says the international community should ease the
conditions of access to multilateral facilities for the heavily
indebted poor countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), in terms of the plight of
the world's developing region, Africa, with one-third of its
population not expected to live beyond the age of 40, receives
significant attention in the annual report.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the U.N. continues to consider the development of
Africa as "a matter of the highest priority".
</P>
<P>
Addressing the decline in official development assistance,
Annan notes that aid has declined over the decade to just 0.22
percent of the gross domestic products (GDP) of industrialized
countries as a whole and 0.19 percent of the GDP of the G-7
countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, all of sub-Saharan Africa received a mere 3 billion
U.S. Dollars of aid, compared to 4 billion Dollars for South
Asia, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The report also gives special emphasis to conflicts. While the
world has been free from large-scale conflicts over the past
year, Annan said that a number of local wars broke out in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Annan said, in Africa, while the restoration of the
democratically elected government of Sierra Leone to power is
cited as a success story, the conflicts in Angola, Guinea-Bissau
and countries in Central Africa like Congo (K) are seen as a
manifestation of the extent to which peace remains precarious.
</P>
<P>
The emergency of conflict between Eritrea and Ethiopia, the
first war between neighboring states for a decade, is also cited
by the report, according to the press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
