<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2005 GMT, September 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's teachers union and the Finance Ministry
have reached an agreement on wage increase following overnight
marathon negotiations, the Jerusalem Post daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has paved the way for the schools to open in the
day after a one-week delay due to teachers' strike for wage rise.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, teachers will get an overall 1.9 percent
real wage increase and additional payments for accompanying school
trips. (BC-Israel-School-Open)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said there is
"little hope" of an agreement between Israel and the Palestinians
on Israel's long-delayed troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Moussa mad the remarks just a day before U.S. Mideast Peace
Coordinator Dennis Ross' arrival in the region to push both
leaders to reach agreement on a U.S. initiative of another 13
percent West Bank withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
"If we judge according to what we listen and read, the hope for
an equitable and just peace would be little," Moussa told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
He added that, however, "we should wait and see how the
situation would be like after Ross' arrival." (BC-Egypt-Mideast
Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi warned
Tuesday that Tehran will resort to any means to seek the release
of Iranian diplomats and other citizens allegedly kidnaped by the
Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi issued the warning to the Taliban at a joint press
conference with his Armenian and Greek counterparts at the end of
the second tripartite meeting of the three countries on trilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the possibility that Tehran would use
force against the Taliban. (BC-Iran-Taliban-Warning)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz warned Tuesday
that Israel's security will face unreasonable risks if defense
budget is not increased.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz made the warning at a meeting of the Foreign Affairs and
Defense Committee of Knesset (Parliament), which began Tuesday to
debate Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai's proposal on the 1999
defense budget, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Mordechai proposed an additional 2 billion
shekels (500 million U.S. dollars) of allocations for the 1999
budget to fund strategic projects.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz said that raising defense budget is essential to the
country's security in short as well as long terms.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israel's defense spending has shrunk in recent
years amid mounting threat from other countries in the Middle
East, such as Iran and Iraq. (BC-Israel-Defense Budget) 
</P>
</TEXT>
