<BODY>
<HEADLINE> English Status in World Goes Down, UK academic Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The exalted status of English
language may be degrading in an ever more integrated global
market, an academic said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are beginning to realize the implications may be moving in
a quite different way," David Graddol of the Open University told
a news conference at the annual science festival in Cardiff, the
capital of Wales in west Britain.
</P>
<P>
He said the development of the global economy, and a trend
towards sophisticated service sectors, had initially favored
English, but now it was at the end of that wave.
</P>
<P>
According to his study, about nine percent of the world's
population spoke English as a first language in 1950, but by the
middle of the next century that will have fallen to about five
percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the number of people who speak English as a
second language is set to overtake the number of native speakers.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the United States, Spanish is becoming a far
more important language as the Hispanic population grows rapidly
and Latin America becomes a more important trading zone, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The rest of the world may speak English but they also speak
other languages and we may have to learn them if we want to reach
their markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
A report last year by the British Council -- whose role is to
promote Britain and English -- forecast rapid growth in the number
of young people around the globe speaking English as a first
language, putting it fourth behind Chinese, Hindi and Arabic by
the middle of the next century and closing the gap.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
