<HEADLINE> U.S. Rejects Lockerbie Lawyer's Call for Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States Tuesday
rejected a call from the chief defense lawer for two Libyan
suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie airline bombing to negotiate a plan
for the trial of them in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that this was
a "nonnegotiable offer."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the remarks by chief defense lawer Ibrahim
Legwell, who said U.S.-British proposals to try his clients in the
Netherlands did not assure them a fair trial and said further
negotiations were needed for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain proposed on Aug. 24 that the two
suspects in the bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie,
Scotland, would be tried in the Netherlands by Scottish judges and
under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
But Legwell said there were a number of conditions which did
not meet the requirements for a fair trial. These included the
court that consists only of Scottish judges, the conditions of
detention of the suspects in the Netherlands before and during the
trial if they went there, and the choice of Britain as the place
of their imprisonment if they were convicted.
</P>
<P>
"Because it calls for a trial in a neutral venue, it is a
positive move. But it must be completed through negotiations,"
Legwell said.
</P>
<P>
"That was a nonnegotiable offer," McCurry said at a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"That was not the basis upon which the government of the United
Kingdom and the government of the United States made the offer,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Britain Tuesday declined to comment on Legwell's remarks.
</P>
<P>
"We have no comment. We've told the Libyans we're not reacting
to matters discussed in the media," said a British official.
</P>
<P>
Both the United States and Britain have said in the past that
their proposals were not negotiable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
