<HEADLINE> Conference on Disarmament Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Conference on Disarmament
(CD) ended its 1998 session here Tuesday with no consensus on
admitting Ecuador, Ireland, Kazakhstan, Malaysia and Tunisia to
the 61-member conference.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of Morocco, Norway, Bangladesh, Algeria,
Sweden, Turkey, Ireland, Malaysia, Ecuador and Tunisia regretted
that the conference was not in a position to approve its expansion
although it was close to reaching a consensus and hoped this
decision could be taken at the start of its 1999 session.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Mark Hofer of Switzerland, the Special Coordinator
on the expansion of membership of the CD, recommended that the
conference appoint a Special Coordinator to continue informal
consultations on this issue in the 1999 session.
</P>
<P>
The conference also adopted the final reports of its Ad Hoc
Committee established to negotiate a ban on the production of
fissile material for nuclear weapons and its Ad Hoc Committee on
negative security assurances.
</P>
<P>
The Conference then adopted its annual report to the General
Assembly and concluded its 1998 session. According to the annual
report, the dates for the 1999 three-phase session will be from 18
January to 26 March, from 10 May to 25 June, and from 26 July to 8
September. The next public plenary would be held on 19 January
1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
