<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Needs 78 Billion Dollars to Fight New Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korea needs 78 billion
U.S. dollars by September 1999 to fight another possible financial
crisis, said a spokesperson for a South Korean think tank.
</P>
<P>
In a report released Wednesday, Samsung Economic Research
Institute predicted that the nation can only accumulate a usable
foreign reserve of some 60 billion dollars by that time.
</P>
<P>
This is short of the currency reserve needed to hold off
another financial crisis possibly by the latter part of 1999.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will need 78 billion dollars, the think tank's
representative said, by next September to fulfill its
international obligations, including interest payments, and to
stem the outflow of foreign portfolio investments.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's usable foreign exchange holdings stood at 41.38
billion dollars last month. The country could be swept up in
another currency crunch if it fails to take the necessary
measures, said the institute.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has to pay 38.1 billion dollars back in foreign
debts, including 15 billion mid-term and long-term debts, 12.2
billion in interest and 10.9 billion in IMF bailout loans.
</P>
<P>
In addition, domestic corporations might be asked to repay
their short-term debts to foreign investment firms, which were
estimated at 26.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Korean firms may have to reimburse their
locally-arranged loans worth 10.5 billion won. Some 2.9 billion
dollars in foreign portfolio investments is likely to flow out of
the country if international investors withdraw 30 percent of
their money.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Economic Research Institute urged the government to
boost international confidence by speeding up corporate and
financial reforms and finalizing the crisis-management system to
stem new waves of financial and economic woes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0060 </DOCNO>
