<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Int'l Marathon '99 to Run Through Dow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following the tremendous success of the Standard Chartered '98
New Airport Marathon, organizers of the 64,000 U.S. dollars race
next year have taken a step further to ensure that an ever bigger
spectacle will occur with a new "urban" course for the February
28, 1999 event.
</P>
<P>
Starting at Chater Road in Hong Kong's Central district, the
42,195-kilometer race will take runners through the Western
Harbor tunnel, along the newly-completed Route 3 Expressway, the
Cheung Tsing Tunnel, across the Ting Kau Bridge and back,
finishing at the Shamshuipo Sports Ground.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a local marathon race will take
place in the urban streets of Hong Kong, which benefits the
public participation at the beginning and end of the race and
ensures that it will add a new experience for local runners.
</P>
<P>
And, apart from the grueling challenge of full marathon, the
popular 10-kilometer race will also be staged alongside the main
event. Runners will start at the Western Park in Hong Kong,
through the Western Harbor tunnel and winding up at the
Shamshuipo Sports Ground.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Marathon inaugurated in 1997 when the race
caught the limelight as it ran across into Shenzhen of Guangdong
Province, with a record field of 1,076 runners from 20 countries
and regions. The successful race was awarded the Merit Award for
the Best Newcomer to Sports Sponsorship by the Hong Kong Sports
Development Board.
</P>
<P>
The Standard Chartered '98 New Airport Marathon was heralded
as another major success, receiving a worldwide coverage as one
of the leading events celebrating the opening of the new Hong
Kong International Airport at Chek Lap Kok. More than 6,400
runners took part in the marathon and the 10-kilometer run at the
record-breaking event.
</P>
<P>
HKAAA wishes to make the Hong Kong marathon a permanent
fixture on the international calendar, and in doing so hope to
one day rival the Boston, London and New York marathon races,
events which have captured the public's imagination as globally
recognized events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
