<HEADLINE> Russia Awaits Yeltsin's Decision on Premier Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia is waiting for President
Boris Yeltsin's decision on whether he will offer a compromise
candidate for prime minister to break the current political
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin met Wednesday with Acting Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and Acting Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov at his
residence outside Moscow, but he has not made a decision on the
prime minister's post, said sources close to the president.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was said to be focused on the current political
situation in the country and the international reaction to current
developments in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin's nomination for premier was rejected by the State
Duma in its second vote on Monday. Under the Russian Constitution,
if the nomination is rejected three times, the president will have
to dissolve the Duma and call new elections within three months.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass news agency quoted Chairman of the State Duma
Gennady Seleznyov as saying that it is a good sign that Yeltsin is
not rushing to nominate a candidate for prime minister following
the Duma's second rejection of Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, Yuri Maslyukov, a State Duma deputy from the
Communist Party and head of the Duma's Economic Policy Committee,
is the best candidate for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, several State Duma deputies have reiterated their
opinion that the appointment of Chernomyrdin as acting prime
minister is illegal.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Lukyanov of the Communist Party faction noted the law
allows the president to select an acting prime minister only from
the group of deputy prime ministers of the dismissed Cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
