<HEADLINE> Clinton Tells Congressional Democrats He's Sorry for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday told congressional Democrats that he was very sorry for
causing pain in his family and throughout the country by his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, news
reports said.
</P>
<P>
"It was an emotional meeting. He wants to carry on with the
business of the country but he clearly understands the deep pain
he has caused," said Representative David Bonior of Michigan,
second-ranking Democrat in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Bonior said there was no discussion of impeachment or
resignation. "I think the president will certainly be able to
continue in office," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting in the White House came days before
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr delivers a report to Congress on
his four-year investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Bonior described Clinton's meeting with Democrats as
"emotional." "What we saw was a father, a husband, the leader of
our country who was contrite, who was very sorry for his actions,"
he was quoted as saying by news reports.
</P>
<P>
Bonior said the handful of Democratic lawmakers present forgave
Clinton for his actions. He said he advised Clinton he needs to
make clear to the American people his contrition and sorrow and
"he needs to address it on a continual basis. But he also needs to
get to the issues he was elected to address in this country."
</P>
<P>
"The American people do not want to see this president fail.
They want to see him succeed," Bonior said. 
</P>
