<HEADLINE> Feature: U.N. Bell Rings for World Peace  (By Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Autumn morning
sunlights are caressing the Peace Bell Pavilion in the complex of
the United Nations headquarters here. Standing in the breeze on
the front lawn, three women are singing for friendship and peace
for the globe.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. flag and national flags of 185 members are flying in
the sunny morning of the 1998 International Peace Day, which falls
on September 9. The audience, representing different cultures and
varying colors, applauded the performance.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan ringed the Peace Bell at 9:30
a.m. (local time), and the bell sang in a universal language --
peace for the world, peace for the mankind.
</P>
<P>
"I appeal, therefore, on the Day of Peace, to all the leaders
of nations in war to set aside their own ambitions and think of
their peoples, to resist the temptation to seek glory through
conquest, and to recognize that peaceful statesmanship alone will
bring them and their peoples the rewards they deserve," Annan said
at the brief ceremony.
</P>
<P>
As the bell rang in the U.N. headquarters, too many parts of
the world are at war. From the Balkans to Central Africa,
innocent men, women and children are the victims of indiscriminate
attacks and are left to a life of despair, dispossession and
exile.
</P>
<P>
The International Peace Day coincides with the opening of the
new General Assembly session, at which governments across the
globe are expected to tell the world how they will strive for
peace and development in the world.
</P>
<P>
"We are very happy to sing songs for peace in the United
Nations headquarters," one of the three female singers from Japan
told Xinhua. She, together with her teacher and classmate, sang
Japanese songs, which are entitled "We are friends," and
"Beautiful Dreamer."
</P>
<P>
"We want the world to build friendship among different
cultures," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
