<HEADLINE> Sudan Makes 20-Million-Dollar Emergency Aid Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
declared a state of emergency and appeal to the international
community for emergency assistance amounting to 20 million U.S.
dollars, said the United Nations Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shelter materials, food and medicines make up the priority
requirements following the floods affecting Sudan's states of
Khartoum, River Nile, Northern Nile, White Nile and Kassala,
leaving about 100,000 people displaced.
</P>
<P>
"Thousands of buildings - homes, houses, schools, roads,
bridges and agricultural assets - have either been washed away or
heavily damaged," said OCHA..
</P>
<P>
According to OCHA, The Sudanese Red Crescent Society, with
support from the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
Crescent (IFRC), will meet the emergency needs of 95,000 victims
in four states for a period of two months. The IFRC has launched
an appeal for food and non-food items, including water pumps,
sprayers, medical equipment, worth two million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program is transporting 17 tons of food to
Kassala from stocks in Gedarif to provide emergency rations to
about 8,000 people for one month.
</P>
<P>
Two UN assessment teams have been dispatched to areas in the
north and south where the situation remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
Funds to aid flood victims in Sudan should be transferred to
OCHA account No. CO-590.160.1, Swift code: SBCOCHGG12A at the UBS
AG. OCHA's website is http://www.reliefweb.int. 
</P>
</TEXT>
