<HEADLINE> Albright Fires Back at Critics of Iraq Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright made a counter-attack on Wednesday at critics
who accused her of easing away from U.S. tough policy on Iraq,
saying "they are sincerely wrong."
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the American war veterans in New Orleans,
Albright said the United States had been the strongest
international backer of U.N. Special Commission, which is
responsible for weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We have pushed and pushed and pushed some more to help UNSCOM
break through the smokescreen of lies and deception put out by the
Iraqi regime," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We have not taken any option off the table, including military
force... The bottom line is that if Iraq tries to break out of its
strategic box, our response will be strong and swift," she added.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration, and Albright in particular, has
been faulted relentlessly in recent weeks by arms expert Scott
Ritter, who charged that the United States undermined the U.N.
Special Commission through "interference and manipulation."
</P>
<P>
The case made by Ritter, who resigned as a U.N. weapons
inspector in Iraq, has been used by senators and editorial writers
to fault administration policy toward Iraq and to question
Albright's credibility. Her speech to the annual American Legion
Convention, was her most sustained rebuttal so far.
</P>
<P>
"In recent weeks, some in Washington have suggested that the
United States has not done enough to support the U.N. inspectors.
It has even been suggested that we have tried to prevent from
doing job," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The critics are sincere... But they are sincerely wrong when
they blame America for the world's failure to uncover the full
truth about Iraq's weapons of mass destruction program," she
added. 
</P>
