<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demarcation Line Proves to Be a Pass to Prosperity (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, nearly 300 business people from the Commonwealth of
Independent States come to the market daily. They usually buy
goods worth 150,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to An Jianzhong, more than 20,000 business people can
make deals simultaneously on the market, which has a business area
of 120,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Horgos had been an important station on the famous "Silk Road"
in the Sui (581-618) and Tang (618-907) dynasties. Russian
businessmen began trading with Yili in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region at the end of the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
Horgos Pass became a trade port between China and Russia in
1881, and turned into a silent place in the "Cold War" period with
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
However, it has begun a new phase of development in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
Qi Xinghai, deputy head of the Horgos Pass Management
Committee, said there were only 58 civilians living there in
1984 besides soldiers guarding the pass, and only 120 people
passed the port every year.
</P>
<P>
Now, the permanent residents there exceed 6,000, with 15,000
people passing through each day.
</P>
<P>
The pass, 290 kilometers to the west of Alma-Ata, has an annual
handling capacity of 3 million tons. The pass is also
well-equipped in terms of infrastructure. It has been named as one
of the 500 best small towns in China by the Ministry of
Construction for two consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Horgos is not only an attraction to business people, but also
to travelers. Nearly 1,000 people visit the place for sightseeing
each day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Bank Seeks to Raise Inter-member Trade by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Islamic
Development Bank (IDB) Ahmad Mohammad Ali said on Wednesday that
the bank is trying to raise the inter-member trade by 13 percent
over next three years, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting starting on Tuesday in Jeddah, Saudi
Arabia, about the bank's export-financing program, Ali expressed
confidence that the goal is attainable provided that strenuous
efforts are exerted to surmount obstacles to trade exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The Jeddah-based IDB includes 52 Islamic countries in the
world. One of its top priorities is to promote inter-member trade,
which is estimated at 10 percent of their total external trade.
</P>
<P>
The bank's program is aimed at financing exports and imports
among the members, creating a portfolio to safeguard investment
and exports credits.
</P>
<P>
The bank announced last month to appropriate 1.4 billion U.S.
dollars to encourage commercial exchanges among member states,
including 830 million dollars for imports, 200 million dollars for
exports and 300 million dollars for the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Since the creation of the export financing program in 1986, the
IDB has earmarked a total of 13 billion dollars to finance trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
