<HEADLINE> S. Asian Countries Meet in Nepal on Women Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The second South Asia
regional meeting, which aims to identify follow-up efforts to the
Fourth World Conference on Women held in Beijing in September
1995, opened here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Those attending the two-day meeting include ministers for women
affairs and secretaries at the women's ministries of the seven
member countries of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of U.N. agencies and leading non-governmental
organizations in the SAARC region are also present at the meeting
organized jointly by the Nepali government and the New Delhi-based
South Asian Regional Office of the United Nations Development Fund
for Women (UNIFEM).
</P>
<P>
UNIFEM said in a press release that the first South Asia
regional meeting held in September 1996 in New Delhi strongly
recommended that such meetings be held every alternate year as
there was a consensus that this process lends considerable
stimulus to the Beijing follow-up efforts in different countries
as well as negotiates space for women's movement.
</P>
<P>
It said that in the post-Beijing South Asia regional scenario,
there have been several initiatives which have been directed
toward the fulfillment of the commitments made at the Beijing
conference.
</P>
<P>
"All South Asian countries have ratified Convention on
Elimination of Discrimination Against Women, and in addition to
the drawing up of national plans of action, there have been
important changes at policy, institutional, political,
programmatic, legal and plan levels," it said.
</P>
<P>
"This meeting will attempt to take a regional overview, share
experiences and best practices, identify gaps and chart actions
for the future, with respect to the Beijing consensus," UNIFEM
said.
</P>
<P>
"An effort will be made to facilitate networking and
inter-regional collaborations on the critical areas of concern,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
A UNIFEM report notes that the greatest burden of human
deprivation and poverty, illiteracy and health-related problems in
South Asia falls on its women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
