<HEADLINE> Taiwan Establishes Nearly 40,000 Enterprises on Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Official figures show that
through June of this year, Taiwan business people had set up
39,821 enterprises on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of approved investment projects from Taiwan
dropped by 5.3 percent in the first half of this year compared
with the same period of last year, according to An Min, assistant
minister of the Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said at a forum held by the Taiwan Studies Society here
today that this could be attributed to the impact of the Asian
financial crisis and Taiwan authorities' policy which creates
obstacles for mainland-bound investors.
</P>
<P>
But he forecast a promising second half, saying that as the
tension between the two sides is relaxing and the investment
environment is getting better, Taiwan investment will increase to
some extent.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the Chinese mainland and Taiwan last year
reached 19.8 billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 4.5 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
An said that the mainland is adopting active measures to
develop cross-Straits economy and trade, and the central
government is unwilling to see Taiwan business people miss such a
good opportunity.
</P>
<P>
He continued to say that the central government will continue to
use Hong Kong as a bridge for the improvement of cross-Straits
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Most economic and trade activities between the mainland and
Taiwan are now carried out via Hong Kong. However, costs have
increased because of this transfer, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
