<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Here Comes Ross Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Middle East peace envoy
Dennis Ross is due here Wednesday afternoon for another visit that
many hope could help make a miracle.
</P>
<P>
On the agenda of his visit are the scope of the long overdue
Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank and the security cooperation
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Following more than a month of bargaining since their direct
talks resumed in July, Israel and the Palestinians have
reportedly reached a draft agreement over another Israeli pullback
after Israel made concessions on other interim issues such as the
airport, the industrial park and the safe passage between the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The draft suggests that Israel pulls back its troops from 13.1
percent more of the West Bank as a U.S. initiative demands but
turns 3 percent into a nature reserve where Israel will retain
full security control.
</P>
<P>
Although the Palestinians have denied lately the existence of
such a draft and called the Israeli proposals as unacceptable,
they are believed to have not backed off from their basic
understanding with Israel.
</P>
<P>
They are withholding a final approval for tactical purposes,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the most substantive gaps remain on the issue of
security cooperation, which constitute an important part of an
overall redeployment package.
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians signed a U.S.-brokered memorandum
of understanding on security last December but Netanyahu rejected
it, saying it was not detailed enough to be effective.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Israel worked out a draft in early July and
presented it to the Palestinians, but the Palestinians snubbed it
because the work was done without consulting them.
</P>
<P>
U.S. security officials have held talks with the Palestinians
in the recent months, trying to reach common ground between the
Palestinian positions and Israeli demands. The issue will soon
prove to be a real challenge to Ross during his visit.
</P>
<P>
The belated visit, amid widespread pessimism over the peace
process and distrust of the U.S. after Washington's bombing of
Afghanistan and Sudan, seems all the more important for all sides
to achieve a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
For the past several months, Netanyahu has been swinging
between his left-wing and right-wing coalition partners, fearing a
decision on redeployment would cause his government famous for its
hardline stance. However, this indecision can not last long.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Oslo process is approaching its end. The accords
that started the peace process five years ago will expire next
May. The two sides have yet to begin the final-status talks, which
are more complicated and more difficult than all the previous ones.
</P>
<P>
Tensions are building up between the two sides the peace
impasse drags on. Last month, three Jewish settlers were murdered
in two incidents in the West Bank, violent clashes broke out
between the Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in Hebron, and a
bomb went off in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
More violence, even with greater magnitude, is in the offing if
no progress is to be made in the peace process soon, many people
warned.
</P>
<P>
And again, the freeze in the talks in the last few days
indicated the two sides have reached a point that they can not
resolve disputes by themselves and a third party is urgently need
to step in.
</P>
<P>
That's why both Israel and the Palestinians welcomed the
decision of U.S. President Bill Clinton to send Ross back to the
region. But for Washington itself, Ross' visit is also vital.
</P>
<P>
Since proposing its initiative on 13.1 percent Israeli
withdrawal early this year, the U.S. has entered a long but
fruitless wrestling with Netanyahu, who vehemently resisted it.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright talked with
Netanyahu on many occasions - in Israel, in London, and in
Washington, and Ross shuttled between Israel and the Palestinians,
but all these ended up in frustration.
</P>
<P>
This had prompted Washington to threaten to wash hands out of
the peace process. It rejected, more than once, appeals from both
Israel and the Palestinians to intervene since they resumed direct
talks. It insisted that it will not mediate until significant
progress has been made.
</P>
<P>
Small wonder that U.S. officials have been trying to downplay
Ross' visit, saying it could narrow much of the gap but an
agreement will not be imminent.
</P>
<P>
Observers predict that Ross will define as his main goal the
arrangement of a summit between Netanyahu and Arafat later this
month when the two are in New York for the General Assembly of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Whether the two leaders could resolve their remaining gaps and
clinch a deal until then is still not a safe bet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
