<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Witnesses Emergence of Entrepreneurial Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- While Chinese people have
traditionally regarded ancestral cemeteries as sacred, farmers in
Yi County, north China's Hebei Province, recently reinterred 35
ancestral graves to make way for the construction of a new market.
</P>
<P>
"Money trees won't grow in the graveyard, but it will
nonetheless in a bustling marketplace," according to villager Luo
Jiageng who recently reinterred the remains of his father.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese farmers have gained a greater awareness of market
functions and adapting to market competition, with a number
emerging as outstanding entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yufen, an entrepreneurial farmer from Xingtai County, Hebei
Province, expanded went into business selling brooms and has since
established a graphite company sales. Liu and another farmer from
Xingdong County, formed a joint venture with fixed assets of over
183 million yuan (22 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"Local government support enabled me to succeed in overcoming
tough competition," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The Hebei government has introduced over 300 policies
encouraging the development of private enterprises since the
1980s, according to Li Jianchang, an official of Hebei Provincial
Industrial and Commercial Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The old management system for rural enterprises was based on
nepotism and greatly hindered the development of the
enterprises. Now, however, entrepreneurial farmers are introducing
scientific systems to their corporations.
</P>
<P>
Eight farmers in Hebei's Qinghe County invested 16 million yuan
to merge their enterprises into a Cashmere Processing Group. They
hired an expert from a state-owned company in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region to serve as general manager, and now have an
annual sales volume of 61.6 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Qinghe County enterprises currently employ over 500
professional staffers.
</P>
<P>
He Yuzhi, deputy secretary-general of the China Private
Enterprises Association, noted that the emergence of modern
entrepreneurial farmers will help to promote the Chinese economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ``Glaciological Research Aids Understanding of Climate, Environment'' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Glaciological research has
provided people with valuable information about the global climate
and environmental changes for the past 50 years, said Dr. Jo
Jacka, vice-chairman of the International Glaciology Society (IGS)
here today.
</P>
<P>
The scientist, who is here for the Sixth International
Symposium on Antarctic Glaciology which closed today, said that
glaciological research will experience an even more fruitful era
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Worldwide scientific research on the subject started in the
1930s, and become a popular topic in global science circles in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Jacka, an Australian scientist famous for his research into
glaciers in polar regions, said that glaciers are able to "record"
the changes of climate and environment in the past, like gigantic
data bases. Scientists can learn about geological, chemical and
climatic changes in ancient times by studying glaciers. Moreover,
from such research, scientists can forecast future climatic and
environmental changes.
</P>
<P>
"Scientists have claimed that the earth's climate is warming
up, and the reason for this phenomenon can be figured out
from glaciological research findings," the expert noted.
</P>
<P>
The temperature has risen by two degrees centigrade worldwide
in the past century, and it may rise at a more rapid rate in the
coming century, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He attributed global warming to the sudden increase in the
amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, which is now about 25
percent higher than it was 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
This results from excessive burning of fossil fuels such as
coal and petroleum, he said, adding that this discovery has
aroused concern among the governments of many countries, which
are now making considerable efforts to control the emission of
carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
The rising temperature has also broken the balance of water on
the earth, he said. He noted that research into this topic will
soon become a focal point for both Chinese and foreign
glaciologists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
