<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Mark Teachers' Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people are busy
preparing for activities on Thursday to mark the annual Teachers'
Day.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference and the
China Association for Promoting Democracy held a gathering in
Beijing today to celebrate the event.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the organizations expressed their greetings to
teachers nationwide, especially those suffered from the summer
floods.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education gave awards to the top 10 outstanding
teachers of the country and excellent teachers who achieved
exploits in the flood fight.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also issued a letter calling on teachers to change
outmoded ways. The old method of teaching involved feeding the
students in the way people feed ducks, which limits independence,
curiosity and creativity in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
On the campus of Nanchang University which is among the flooded
areas, students and teachers held a charity theatrical performance
to raise money for flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Another show will held by China Central Television and the
Ministry of Education Thursday evening to raise more money for
rebuilding damaged schools and providing subsidies for displaced
students.
</P>
<P>
China's first Teachers' Day was launched in 1985 in an effort
to create an atmosphere of respect for teachers, whose importance
was ignored in the chaotic Cultural Revolution (1966-'76).
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping cleared teachers' names and used them to propel
the modernization of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
