<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Concerned about Super-League Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
expressed its concern over the planned European super-league
soccer tournament and would like to make sure the planning is
compatible with its competition rules.
</P>
<P>
European Competition Commissioner Karel van Miert demanded
more detailed information about the plans from Milan-based Media
Partners, the consortium behind the ambitious and controversial
plan.
</P>
<P>
The take-off of the proposed super-league tourney needs
commission clearance.
</P>
<P>
Media Partners head Rodolfo Hecht has promised van
Miert,according to Wednesday's issue of the journal European
Report, to provide detailed information for the proposed league
of Europe's top clubs.
</P>
<P>
The journal quoted Hecht as saying that he planned to notify
the European Commission early on to pre-empt any competition
concerns about cartels and the collective sale of television
rights.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to brief the commissioner on such issues as
the potential exclusive long-term broadcasting contracts and
discriminatory membership rules.
</P>
<P>
Media Partners has claimed that their project would be fully
compatible with European Union's competition law and would give
all clubs in Europe the chance to take part.
</P>
<P>
Apart from free, terrestrial television broadcasts, the
consortium added, pay-per-view, digital and the Internet will
also be used to maximize access to the soccer fans and revenues
so generated to the clubs.
</P>
<P>
The Union of European Football Associations, the governing
body of the sport on the continent, has been worried by the
super-league planning and is desperate to retain its rights over
European club matches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
