<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Further Ease Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Japan (BOJ) decided
Wednesday to further ease its grip on credit by guiding short-term
interest rates lower to quell fears about the country's financial
system, BOJ Governor Masaru Hayami said.
</P>
<P>
With this new monetary stance, the Japanese central bank will
seek to keep the unsecured overnight call money rate at around
0.25 percent per annum on a weighted average basis, down from the
current 0.4-0.5 percent, Hayami told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Our primary concern is the further worsening of the real
economy... We judged that easier credit is appropriate to help
stabilize the country's financial health," he said.
</P>
<P>
The overnight call money rate is the rate at which financial
institutions lend surplus funds to other financial institutions
that need money to fund their activities.
</P>
<P>
The call money market is where financial institutions lend each
other money and take out call loans maturing in the short term.
</P>
<P>
The market is the most important place where commercial banks
can raise funds to finance their daily lending and
deposit-refunding activities, while allowing financial
institutions with surplus funds to capitalize on interest accruing
from the call money they lend.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's decision to guide short-term money market
rates lower is the first monetary relaxation move the BOJ has
conducted in three years.
</P>
<P>
The BOJ's latest decision is aimed at preventing global stock
market turbulence induced by the Russian financial turmoil from
disrupting Japan's banking system, while providing additional
monetary stimuli to the stalled domestic economy, financial
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Following the announcement of the BOJ's easier monetary policy,
the U.S. dollar surged 3 yen to the upper 136 yen level Wednesday
evening in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
In London, the dollar jumped more than 4 yen to hit the mid-137
yen level at one point in early trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
