<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Denies Arrest of NLD Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government denied
Wednesday that it has arrested members of the National League for
Democracy (NLD), according to an official Information Sheet issued
here Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
In response to Tuesday's remarks of James Rubin, spokesman of
the State Department of the United States, regarding Myanmar's
detention of opposition figures, the information sheet claimed "no
member of the NLD has been arrested or charged with any crime.
Some members of the NLD have been invited by the government to
help ensure a peaceful transition to a multi-party democracy."
</P>
<P>
It added that "the NLD members have been very cooperative and
are being comfortably housed in government guest houses."
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar government also denied that it has threatened to
deport Aung San Suu Kyi, general secretary of the NLD.
</P>
<P>
"The government has an obligation to protect the rights of all
Myanmar citizens to a safe, secure environment," the Information
Sheet said.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Myanmar welcomes any efforts by the U.S. and
the international community to help Myanmar maintain the current
stability during its transition to a multi-party democracy," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The NLD has repeatedly demanded the convening of a parliament
elected in the 1990 General Election in accordance with the then
Election Law and on June 23 set a deadline for the ruling State
Peace and Development Council (SPDC) to hold the parliament within
60 days.
</P>
<P>
After it received no response from the government on the expiry
of the deadline on August 21, the NLD declared its intention to
convene the parliament by itself in September.
</P>
<P>
The government had also warned earlier that "it would amount to
the NLD making herself a parallel government which no government
in the world would accept."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NLD charged on Wednesday's statement that the
Myanmar government has detained 187 parliament
representatives-elect and 334 organizers of the party since May
27, the 8th anniversary of Myanmar's General Election.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 58 NLD parliament-representatives-elect and 160 party
organizers have so far been detained after the party declared to
hold the parliament by itself on expiry of the deadline.
</P>
<P>
The NLD won the majority vote in the 1990 General Election,
participated by 93 political parties, with 396 out of the 485
parliamentary seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
