<HEADLINE> China Welcomes Overseas Business to Renovate State Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
that the government will continue to encourage foreigners to
invest in and renovate the country's state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"We especially welcome foreign investors in east China to
participate in the improvement of big and medium-sized state
enterprises in middle and west China," said Meng Xiangang, deputy
secretary-general of the State Economy and Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
He told participants at a forum on attracting overseas
investment held here today that China is adopting a policy
encouraging state enterprises to actively use overseas capital to
readjust their strategy and reorganize their estates.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has allowed overseas investors to buy, rent
or run small state enterprises, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has 14,800 large and medium-size state enterprises, and
480,000 small ones. Many of them are running in the red, he
said. The Chinese government has vowed to solve their difficulties
within three years.
</P>
<P>
Meng said that the reform of state enterprises presents
opportunities for overseas investment. In the coming years, the
government expects overseas businesses to update the technologies
of China's old industrial bases and conventional industries.
</P>
<P>
He said that direct overseas investment will be the main
channel in the renovation, in addition to overseas loans and stock
issues in an adequate and cautious way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
