<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Delays Decision Against Italy's Airport Sharing Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
Wednesday delayed a decision against Italy for its plan to share
airline services and traffic between two airports in the city of
Milan.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, told the Italian government that it would meet again next
Wednesday to see what kind of decision needed to be taken.
</P>
<P>
European Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock said: "It is my
duty to uphold European law and to protect the competitive
interests of European air carriers and their passengers."
</P>
<P>
The commission was scheduled to decide against the Italian
sharing plan Wednesday, but changed the schedule after Kinnock
received a phone call from the Italian transport minister.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Italian government decided to distribute airline
traffic between Milan's existing airport Linate and the new
airport Malpensa, which is due to open on October 25.
</P>
<P>
Under a decree by Italian authorities, all carriers with more
than two million passengers each year will continue to fly in and
out of the easily-accessible Linate. Other flights will have to
fly out of Malpensa, which is 53 kilometers away from Milan.
</P>
<P>
Nine European carriers, including British Airways, Iberia, TAP,
Sabena, Lufthansa, Air France, Olympic, Austria Airlines and SAS
have complained to the European Commission that the plan is
discriminatory and disproportionate.
</P>
<P>
The carriers argued that due to the lack of sufficient
infrastructure between Milan and Malpensa, passengers would
continue to choose to fly Italy's national carrier Alitalia, out
of Linate, which is close to downtown Milan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Runaway Consumption Widens Gap Between Rich, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Runaway consumption in the
world has been widening the gap between rich and poor and gross
inequalities in consumption opportunities have excluded over one
billion people who fail to meet even their basic consumption
requirements.
</P>
<P>
The report for 1998, commissioned by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) and launched Wednesday worldwide, says
that 86 percent of expenditures of personal consumption are made
by just 20 percent of the world population.
</P>
<P>
These rich people consume 45 percent of all the meat and fish,
58 percent of total energy, and 84 percent of all paper, and have
74 percent of all telephone lines and 87 percent of the world's
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the poorest one-fifth of the world population
consumes only 5 percent of meat and fish, less than 4 percent of
energy, and 1.1 percent of paper and have 1.5 percent of
telephone lines and less than 1 percent of cars.
</P>
<P>
The unequal income distribution translates into social
exclusion when the social values place too much importance on
what a person possesses rather than what a person is or can do,
the report says.
</P>
<P>
It warns that when social standards rise faster than incomes,
consumption patterns become unbalanced. Household spending for
conspicuous consumption can crowd out such essentials as food,
education, health care, child care and saving for a secure
future.
</P>
<P>
Runaway growth in consumption is placing unprecedented
pressure on the environment and putting those who consume least
in double jeopardy. Poor people benefit least and suffer the
most painful consequences of the unsustainable consumption
habits.
</P>
<P>
"The poorest one-fifth of the world's population, who are
responsible for just three percent of carbon dioxide emissions,
live in low-lying regions that are most vulnerable to the rising
sea levels associated with global warming," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Consumers, civil society and governments are urged to forge
alliances for new patterns of consumption and the world needs
patterns of consumption that share resources, not divide
societies, that strengthen people's capacities, not diminish
them, Richard Jolly, the principal coordinator of the report was
quoted by a handout as saying here.
</P>
<P>
The key goals of the report are: raising the consumption
levels of more than one billion people who have been left out of
the consumption boom; moving to more sustainable consumption
patterns; protecting and promoting the rights of consumers;
achieving more equitable burden-sharing among nations to reduce
and prevent damage to environment and reduce poverty itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
