<HEADLINE> UNICEF Appeals for Emergency Aid for Bangladeshi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) on Wednesday made an appeal for emergency assistance
of 8 million U.S. Dollars for Bangladeshi women and children
affected by the current devastating flood.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF representative in Dhaka Shahida Azfar, who made the
appeal at a press conference here, said the appeal concentrates on
providing emergency relief to the most vulnerable - children and
women - particularly the landless and homeless during the floods
and in the immediate post-flood period.
</P>
<P>
Of the funding requirements, 1 million-dollar emergency aid is
for food, 4.35 million dollars for health, 2.2 million dollars for
water and environmental sanitation and the rest for replacing
school textbooks and others, she said.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the appeal by UNICEF as part of the wider UN
appeal is to solicit contributions for emergency relief and
rehabilitation of people affected by the flooding in Bangladesh,
the country representative said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the ongoing flood as "the most severe floods in
living memory," Azfar said the already poor nutritional status of
children and women will deteriorate even further as the situation
in many districts is continuing to deteriorate even after at least
of seven weeks of the severe flooding.
</P>
<P>
More than 21 million people are severely affected - either
displaced or made homeless, while some emergency shelters, which
have been set up mostly in schools, are overcrowded, she said.
</P>
<P>
The overcrowding, combined with shortages of food, safe
drinking water and adequate safe sanitation facilities, is almost
the "perfect breeding ground" for the outbreak of major diseases
and public health crisis, she said.
</P>
<P>
She cautioned that the chances of one or more epidemics will
increase even further when the flooding water begins to recede.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
