<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislator Deprived of Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Legislator Chim Pui-chung,
who has been sentenced to a three-year imprisonment by the court,
was relieved here Wednesday of his duties as a member of the
Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Legislative Council President Rita Fan at
a meeting of the council in the Legislative Council Chamber
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The resolution to deprive Chim of his membership was moved by
council member Leong Che-hung under article 79 (6) of the Basic
Law of the HKSAR. The resolution was approved by members of the
Legislative Council with 45 in favor and one abstention.
</P>
<P>
Chim, 51, was convicted on August 1 in the Court of First
Instance of the High Court of conspiracy to forge 199 transfer
documents to help the sale of shares in one of his companies.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that a member of the Legislative
Council is no longer qualified for the office when he or she is
convicted and sentenced to imprisonment for one month or more for
a criminal offense committed within or outside the region and he
or she shall be relieved of his or her duties by a motion passed
by two-thirds of the members of the Legislative Council present.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the council also approved the Holidays
(Amendment) Bill 1998, which was introduced by the government into
the council on July 8, 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the bill, two of the general holidays observed in
1997 and 1998 -- Sino-Japanese War Victory Day (the third Monday
in August) and October 2 (the day after National Day) should be
replaced by Labor Day and the Buddha's Birthday from 1999 onwards.
</P>
</TEXT>
