<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Reiterates Demilitarization of Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRAND BAIE, Mauritius, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Kaire Mbuende,
Executive Secretary of the Southern African Development
Community, reiterated here Wednesday the demilitarization of
politics in the case of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
"Soldiers belong to the barracks and not to the competence in
parliament," the executive secretary said at a press briefing
here in the north of Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
"We are interested in peace and tranquility in that country
(DRC), therefore, we'll do everything possible to assist the
process by supporting and encouraging the government to negotiate
to be accommodated and to set a very clear timetable for
transition to democracy," said Mbuende, who is also Deputy
Minister of Agriculture of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The SADC would like to see democratization in Congo as soon as
possible, he said, adding the regional grouping will encourage
its member states to support materially or financially to
facilitate the process of transition to democracy in the vast
central African country.
</P>
<P>
According to him, if the rebels are clarified in their
attempts of demands, then it is easy to ask the government to
meet the demands, and "the only demand that will make sense if
you are attempting to overthrow the government is to make a
demand for transition to democracy. But that is not their
demands."
</P>
<P>
"What they are trying to do is to take over power through
force and this cannot be allowed," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende has confirmed that a delegation led by Congolese
Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo are coming for the two-day
meeting of Council of Ministers starting Thursday and that
President Laurent Kabila will attend the SADC summit scheduled on
September 13-14.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no representative from the rebel side," he
said. "Congo has a government which is led by President Kabila.
That's the government we are supporting," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Kabila agreed Monday to a cease-fire, but refused
to meet face-to-face with the rebel movement known as the
Congolese Democratic Coalition, leaving peace prospects in the
air.
</P>
<P>
"The source of the Congolese problem is three decades of
protracted dictatorship since independence," Earnest Wamba dia
Wamba, head of the rebel coalition, said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The rebels started an armed revolt on August 2 in Goma, east
Congo, against Kabila's government. They accused Kabila of
corruption, nepotism and authoritarianism.
</P>
<P>
The rebellion soon spread to the west of Congo, even on the
verge of capturing capital Kinshasa, before Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia intervened militarily and turned the tide over.
</P>
<P>
The Congo crisis will be on the SADC summit agenda, with
Kabila expected to brief the heads of state from the 14 member
countries of SADC on the developments in his country.
</P>
<P>
Congo (K) joined the regional organization last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
