<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Rise on Singapore Stock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
rise for the Third consecutive trading day on Singapore Stock
Market Wednesday as the benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) gained
16.78 points to end at 885.46 points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover shot up to 592.30 million units valued at
280.76 million Singapore dollars (162.83 million U.S. dollars).
Advancers outnumbered decliners by 256 to 94 with 237 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong was the most active stock of the day with a volume of
38.35 million stocks traded. It was followed by MBF Cap that had
28.52 million units done. Public Bk F was next with 22.77 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
SPH topped the gainers of the day as it gained 80 cents to
close at 13.40 Singapore dollars. Genting 200 rose by 56 cents to
finish at 2.55 Singapore dollars. M Bank 200 moved up 51.5 cents
to end 1.42 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Rothmans M was the biggest loser of the day as
it registered a decline of 1.5 Singapore dollars. Oriental lost 98
cents to close at 1.60 Singapore dollars. Shell was down 26 cents
to end at 1.44 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said today's rally was encouraged by Wall Street's
gains overnight.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that trading today was dominated by CLOB, which
was resumed for one week after days of suspension and thereafter
trading of Malaysian stocks will cease in the over-the-counter
market in Singapore
</P>
<P>
CLOB stocks accounted for about three quarters of today's heavy
volume, they said.
</P>
<P>
The week is actually the last chance for local brokers to churn
commission in Malaysian shares before ceasing transactions of
Malaysian stocks and giving the business to Malaysian brokers.
</P>
<P>
Although uncertainties still existed over how the shares will
be transferred to Malaysia, dealers said retail investors were
picking up the deeply discounted CLOB shares for profits. 
</P>
