<HEADLINE> China to Further Open Market to Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official
announced here today that China will further open its market to
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi Guangsheng, minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, overseas investment will be allowed in the
service industry, tourism, water transportation, and mining
exploration.
</P>
<P>
The sectors of finance and telecommunications will open to
overseas business on a trial basis, he revealed at a forum to
discuss attracting overseas investment, adding that China will
urge petrochemical and construction industries to use more
overseas capital.
</P>
<P>
In addition, overseas business people are encouraged to invest
in the sectors of agriculture, high-tech, infrastructure,
environmental protection and export-oriented industries as the
country is improving its industrial structure, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will attract overseas investment to the central and west
areas where the opening might be wider and the limitations fewer
than the east part, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to attract investment from Hong Kong,
Taiwan and Macao, as well as Southeast Asian countries, while
increasing its capability to woo capital from North America, Japan
and the European Community.
</P>
<P>
The investment from transnational companies will be welcomed,
he said, adding that cooperation between Chinese state-owned
enterprises and overseas companies will be expanded.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the improvement of the investment environment
and strengthening the management of overseas firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
