<HEADLINE> U.N. Report: 15 Percent Live in Poverty in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- About 15 percent of the
British population live in poverty and nearly 10 percent are not
expect to live to 60, according to a U.N. report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued by the United Nations Development Program,
says deprivation, unemployment and low literacy levels make
Britain one of the most poverty-stricken countries among developed
nations.
</P>
<P>
UNDP's poverty index shows that Britain is ranked 14th --
behind countries such as Germany, Japan and Australia, and only
the Republic of Ireland and the U.S. suffer higher levels of
poverty than Britain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than a fifth of adults in Britain are
considered functionally illiterate while 13.5 percent were living
below the recognized level of the poverty line - half the median
personal disposable income.
</P>
<P>
After taking in to account life expectancy, knowledge
deprivation and social exclusion, the report says 15 percent of
the British population live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
The report also points out that the gap between rich and poor
is growing across the world, with 20 percent of the world's
population consuming 86 percent of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N., global consumption will top 24 trillion
U.S. dollars this year, six times the figure for 1975, as people
consume more food, energy, transportation, communications services
and entertainment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
