<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Host 17th Festival of Asian Arts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Urban
Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
announced here Wednesday that the 17th Festival of Asian Arts will
be held between October 23 and November 14 in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The event organized by the Provisional Urban Council biennially
was "not only a wealth of Asian arts, but also a tribute to Asian
cultures by showcasing their rich heritage, while at the same
time, juxtaposing the old and new, traditional and contemporary to
explore new dimensions," said Patrick Ho Chi-ping, provisional
urban councilor of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
This year's festival features over 16 performing groups from 13
Asian countries and regions to present a spectrum of art forms
including dance, music and theater, he said.
</P>
<P>
The programs this year have been tailored-made and based on
four themes -- Ethnic Traditions, Cross-Cultural Highlights,
Contemporary Theater and Splendor of Local Arts, Ho said.
</P>
<P>
The theme of Ethnic Traditions, he said, would feature
performing groups which strive to nurture age-old art forms so as
to enrich the experiences of modern audiences and cultivate their
interests in cultural history.
</P>
<P>
The theme of Cross-Cultural Highlights would showcase
productions by groups with different cultural backgrounds working
together to achieve common goals, Ho said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Echoes of the Silk Road is a joint project
by music scholars of China and Japan to reconstruct and restore
ancient Chinese instruments transported to Japan via the Silk Road
over a thousand years ago.
</P>
<P>
The third theme is Contemporary Theater that builds on
combining classical and modern dance and music forms with
contemporary staging.
</P>
<P>
Splendor of Local Arts assumes the fourth theme which is a
feast of Hong Kong productions in various art forms.
</P>
<P>
During the Festival, an exciting outdoor program "Asian Arts
Parade" will be staged over three weekends to give a colorful
extravaganza of dance, music, drama and traditional arts performed
by expatriates in Hong Kong from across Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Festival will be complemented by a series of talks, lecture
demonstrations, exhibitions, workshops and outdoor presentations
by participating groups for the Festival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
