<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Investigate on Car Mafia Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Minister of Finance
Fouad Siniora Wednesday said the country will soon open an
investigation into an alleged mafia network smuggling stolen
European cars into Lebanon, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He said to the radio that "there is definitely a mafia network
smuggling stolen cars into Lebanon and we will follow up the case
all the way to the end."
</P>
<P>
He added that more details of the story will be known after he
returns from a three-day visit to Cairo beginning on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese minister's comments came a day after the country's
largest Arab-language newspaper An Nahar revealed that there was
a mafia in the country which is smuggling sedan cars stolen
in various European countries, especially Germany, to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted well-known sources as saying that Lebanese
political figures are using their influence to make sure
the stolen cars to pass through customs without any problems.
</P>
<P>
It also obtained a copy of a report of the international
Police (Interpol) Organization addressed to the Lebanon's customs
management, saying Lebanon has the highest rate of car theft
in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
But the report added that the cooperation of the Lebanese
customs authorities with Interpol has made it possible to
intercept some of the stolen cars before or at their arrival in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Lebanese customs authorities, in
cooperation with Interpol, have recently seized some 75
Mercedes-600 sedan cars allegedly stolen from European
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
