<HEADLINE> Demarcation Line Proves to Be a Pass to Prosperity (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Horgos River was made the
official demarcation line between China and Kazakhstan this
spring. However, the dividing line does not block exchanges
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
As the leaders of the two nations hoped, people on both sides
of the Horgos Pass, the largest land trade port in western China,
are enjoying increasing prosperity since the opening of a border
trade market six years ago.
</P>
<P>
The trade market, which handles nearly 2 million yuan (240,000
U.S. dollars) of commodities daily, has become the largest foreign
wholesale market in west China. The market attracts some 10,000
visitors every day.
</P>
<P>
An Jianzhong, an official in charge of market management, said
that more than 15,000 businessmen from the Commonwealth of
Independent States visited the market in the first six months this
year, with the trade volume reaching 280 million yuan (33.73
million U.S. dollars), an increase of 40 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
People coming to the market include those from inland areas of
China, Kazakhstan and other countries speaking various languages.
</P>
<P>
Baesyry, 49, used to be saleswoman in a department store in
Alma-Ata, capital of Kazakhstan. She has come to the market twice
weekly since 1995.
</P>
<P>
She expressed confidence in her business. She said that some
people earn less money because they know less about the demands on
the market, but that she never heard about people losing money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PTA Firm Urged to Finance Against Capital Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) has challenged its regional
reinsurance company to step up its efforts to mobilize financial
resources to stem cash outflow from the region.
</P>
<P>
According to the Times of Zambia newspaper published here
Wednesday, Kabeta Muleya, director of administration and finance
of the Lusaka-based regional group, made the challenge in a
message released to the paper Tuesday reacting to the performance
of the PTA Reinsurance Company,
</P>
<P>
PTA which stands for the Preferential Trade Area for Eastern
And Southern Africa is the predecessor of COMESA, a 20-member
regional body aiming to achieve a free trade area by the end of
2000.
</P>
<P>
Muleya said that for a long time the COMESA region had
depended on foreign institutions to mobilize financial resources
which should not be left unchecked as substantial resources had
been siphoned outside the region.
</P>
<P>
The PTA firm and other financial institutions should,
therefore, work toward mobilizing more financial resources for
the region to end capital flight, said Muleya.
</P>
<P>
"Regional financial institutions ought to play an important
role in stemming the outflow of resources from our region," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Muleya commended the recent ratification of the protocol on
the relaxation and eventual elimination of visa requirements by
some member countries.
</P>
<P>
He observed that regional trade could only be increased if
there was free movement of people within the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
