<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Influx of Foreign Capital (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's efforts to attract
foreign investment has yielded dividends over the past two years,
with the declining trend giving way to rebounding growth during
the first seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
China signed foreign investment contracts valued at 28.18
billion US dollars during the period, up 7.25 percent on an annual
basis, according to Shi Guangsheng, minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, who is attending the Second China Investment
and Trade Fair.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, China adopted a series of measures to
encourage foreign investment, including granting duty-free status
to imported equipment and related tariff exemptions.
</P>
<P>
The main goals of the efforts centered on attracting
multinational corporations and consortia from the United States
and Europe, and offsetting the negative effects the Asian
financial crisis has had on China's use of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
China continued to lead the world in spite of the marginal
rebound, especially when compared with the dramatic currency
devaluations and economic recessions in many Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The trade fair had yielded more than 1,200 contracts valued at
5.6 billion US dollars by this afternoon, with the volume
indicating the continuing great interest foreign investors have
for doing business in China.
</P>
<P>
Predictions of the foreign media made earlier this year that
the Asian financial crisis would adversely affect the flow of
foreign capital into China have proved erroneous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Head Proposes to Set Up Regional Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Given the prevailing economic
situation in Asia, it is time to establish a regional institution
to finance and promote trade through export credit and credit
guarantee, Adrianus Mooy, executive secretary of United Nation's
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP),
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at the tenth meeting of the Steering Group
of the Committee for Regional Economic Cooperation of ESCAP, which
was held here from Wednesday to Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The idea was to help developing countries with risk
assessment, improve their access to quality information and
financial resources, and achieve economies of scales," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the current economic crisis across the region,
Mooy said any sustained recovery was unlikely to begin before the
end of 1999, even on the most optimistic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
He said the crisis significantly dampens the prospects for the
region's industrial development and technology transfer as it
changes the expectations with respect to profits, forces a premium
on investment in the emerging markets and reduces the supply of
foreign direct investment from developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, opportunities still exist and one needs to reach
beyond the obvious and see what the implications are for the
future, he said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting of the Steering Group will deal with
various aspects of intraregional and interregional trade, trade
facilitation and the integration of transitional economies.
</P>
<P>
The Steering Group is a "think tank" of the ESCAP's Committee
on Regional Economic Cooperation comprising representatives of
governments, the private sector and academia. Its main task is to
develop innovative approaches to topical issues relating to
economic cooperation and make specific recommendations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
