<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Has Poor Consumption Pattern: UNDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's consumption pattern
is among the poorest in the world and needs radical restructuring
for improvement, the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
says in its latest Report for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report, officially launched here and in more than 100
cities around the globe Wednesday morning, puts Uganda in the
160th position of the 174 countries listed in order of life
expectancy, educational attainment and adjusted real income.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, some 30 billion Ugandan shillings (30 million U.S.
Dollars) was spent on basic education while 75 and 145 billion
shillings (75 and 145 million Dollars) were used to buy
cigarettes and alcohol, UNDP Resident Representative in Uganda
Babatunde Thomas told audience at the launching ceremony of the
report.
</P>
<P>
Because of increasing pollution in Lake Victoria, fish catch
has been declining sharply since 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to the Poverty Eradication Action Plan in 1997, 66.3
percent of Uganda's population were living in abject poverty and
86.2 percent living in relative poverty.
</P>
<P>
The life expectancy of less than 50 years reflects a national
waste and the nearly 40 percent of illiteracy describes low
social development.
</P>
<P>
Francis Ayume, Uganda's Parliament speaker, said in a keynote
speech at the ceremony that Ugandans should be more aware of the
impact of consumption on the environment and human development.
</P>
<P>
The government's poverty eradication action plan will focus on
roads, land, agriculture, employment and labor productivity, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP has started to publish its annual report since 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
