<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upper Reaches of Yangtze Prone to More Natural Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The State Forestry
Administration revealed today that an increasing number of natural
disaster are occuring in the Three Gorges Dam area and upper
reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
"The increasing frequency can largely be attributed to
deforestation in the related dam area and upper reaches of
the Yangtze," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan and Guizhou provinces in the upper reachs of the
Yangtze River have suffered from frequent flooding in recent
years, with the annual 1.93 million hectares of flooded areas
recorded for the two provinces in the 1990s rising by as much as
one-fold in the 1980s and a dramatic nine-fold on figures for the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
The report indicted that the forest coverage in the upper
reaches of the Yangtze in Yunnan Province has dropped dramatically
from 50 percent during the 1950s to only 24 percent today. Soil
erosion has jumped dramatically from only 6.3 percent of the total
land coverage in 1956 to the current 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated that some 100 counties in the upper
and middle reaches of the river have completed afforestation
efforts on barren mountains since China initiated the shelterbelt
project in 1989. The extensive project has greatly improved the
ecological environment and enabled related areas to initially
control soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
"It will extremely difficult to reach the percentage of forest
coverage in the 1950s," said the report, adding that over half of
the total number of counties in the Three Gorges areas and upper
reaches of the Yangtze have not as yet introduced the shelterbelt
project." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
