<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encourages Influx of Foreign Capital (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Many foreign investors have turned to China despite low
investment costs in Southeast Asian countries. They, in fact,
believe that China's stable economic and political environments
will offer long-term benefits," according to Wang Zhile, a
research fellow with the China International Trade and Economic
Cooperation Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Economists attribute the continuing influx of foreign
investment mainly to the favorable policies China has adopted this
year. They cite the central government's deliberate investment
guidance for the central and western regions and the booming
service sector as examples.
</P>
<P>
Various United Nations trade development experts contend that
China's market continues to offer vast potential for foreign
investment in spite of perceived market saturation and
insufficient domestic demand. They also note the country will
continue to use large amounts of direct foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
China recorded seven percent growth in GDP for the first seven
months of the year, a mere one point below the annual target. The
country continued to rank first in the world with a foreign trade
volume reaching 179.49 billion US dollars, a year-on-year rise of
4.2 percent, according to recent statistics.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors have exhibited great confidence in China's
long-term and sustainable economic growth, said economists, adding
that the country will maintain GDP growth of at least seven for
the next 12-odd. They also point out that China total investment
scale of 1.2 trillion US dollars will continue to offer vast
business opportunities for foreign investors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
