<HEADLINE> EU Provides Kosovo With 5 Million Ecus in Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has
decided to provide the Yugoslav province of Kosovo with another 5
million ecus (5.5 million U.S. dollars) in emergency humanitarian
aid.
</P>
<P>
The aid will be used to help the displaced people in Kosovo,
according to Wednesday's issue of the journal European Report.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken during an informal meeting by European
Union foreign ministers who met last weekend in Salzburg, Austria,
to discuss issues concerning Russia, the Democratic Republic of
Congo and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The EU fund will cover the reconstruction of village houses
destroyed during armed conflicts between the security forces of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and members of the Kosovar
Liberation Army consisted of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
European Commission President Jacques Santer, who was also
present at the September 5-6 Salzburg meeting, said: "If there is
no cease-fire, we will be faced with a humanitarian disaster as
winter draws nigh."
</P>
<P>
The journal also quoted European Humanitarian Aid Commissioner
Emma Bonino as saying that some 50,000 people are now living in
makeshift shelters in Kosovar forests and mountains with winter
fast approaching.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers debated on what attitude to take toward
Belgrade and the debate displayed opinion differences between
Germany, Austria, the Nordic countries and Greece, France, Britain.
</P>
<P>
The former were advocating tough sanctions against Belgrade
whereas the latter took a less hardline stance, the journal
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
