<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian, Cuban Consortia Sign MOU for Commercial  Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A consortium of Malaysian
companies Wednesday signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU)
with a consortium of Cuba in efforts to enhance cooperation in
commercial activities, especially in the fields of bio-technology
and pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
The MOU was signed between the parties in Johor Baharu, capital
of the southern state of Johor in witness of Johor State Chief
Minister Abdul Ghani Othman and Cuba's Deputy External Trade
Minister Sir Orlando Hernandez Guillen, the Malaysian national
news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
The MOU would enable both parties to conduct research on
technical and financial competitiveness to identify the suitable
sector which could be established jointly, Abdul Ghani said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian consortium was led by Johor state government
through its investment company Yayasan Pelajaran Johor Holdings
Sdn Bhd with the cooperation of Chemical Company of Malaysia, and
two other companies -- Floreat Enterprise Inc and Kumpulan Sungai
Chat while the consortium from Cuba was led by its Bio-Technology
and Genetics Engineering Centre (CIGB).
</P>
<P>
Cuba is the pioneer in the field of bio-technology, genetics
engineering and pharmacy development, has expertise in the
treatment of hypertension and arteriosclerosis and vaccine for
meningitis and hepatitis, and is well known for its treatment of
tropical diseases like dengue, the Johor state chief said.
</P>
<P>
The six-member Cuban delegation led by Orlando is on a
three-day visit to Johor since Monday during which it visited
University Teknologi Malaysia (Technology University Malaysia) in
Skudai, Johor, to see research and development activities in the
fields of bio-technology and genetics engineering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
