<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Third Longest River to Grow Longer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese textbooks may have to
rewrite their accounts of the Huaihe River in a few years later,
because this third longest river of China is expected to become
163.5 kilometers longer.
</P>
<P>
China plans to invest nearly four billion yuan (about 482
million U.S. dollars) to dig an east-west water course in east
China's Jiangsu Province, enabling the water of the Huaihe River
to empty into the Yellow Sea instead of flowing into the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official recently announced that the trial dig
will start this winter, and once completed, the Huaihe River is
expected to become longer than it is today.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe, 1,000 kilometers long, originates in the Tongbai
Mountain in central China's Henan Province, and has a drainage
area of 187,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a century ago, the Yellow River, China's second longest
river, overflowed and took over the Huaihe River's course to the
sea, forcing it to crowd into the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the river has threatened the life and property of
people living along its middle and lower reaches, and in 1991, a
flood there caused heavy losses in Jiangsu province and the
neighboring Anhui and Henan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Experts have conducted many field studies in the region and
submitted several draft resolutions to the central government.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission recently approved the
building of this new water course.
</P>
<P>
Several more water conservation projects will also be built in
the region to assist flood control, the official added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
