<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumption to Be Adjusted for Human Development: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The global consumption
patterns have to be restructured for better human development, a
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) report has said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 UNDP report, which has been launched Wednesday in
more than 100 cities around the world, was officially launched
here by Ugandan Parliament Speaker Francis Ayume, UNDP Resident
Representative in Uganda Babatunde Thomas and other senior
officials of the U.N. agency.
</P>
<P>
The international community has to adjust the current
consumption pattern in order to better help develop the quality
of human beings.
</P>
<P>
There are glaring distortions in the consumption patterns, the
report points out. People now spend so much on entertainment and
on other purposes while very little money is spent to meet their
basic needs.
</P>
<P>
The world spends some six billion U.S. Dollars annually on
basic education while a total of 50 billion Dollars are spent on
cigarettes in Europe alone.
</P>
<P>
The international expenditure on water and sanitation is nine
billion Dollars while Europeans and Americans spend 17 billion
Dollars on pet foods.
</P>
<P>
Media organizations are therefore urged to do more to educate
people in this aspect by promoting information flow to the
grassroots.
</P>
<P>
The impressive impact of consumption on environment is also
stressed in the report. The developed countries, who produce more
pollutants, should work together with poorer countries in
fighting environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
Only when the current consumption pattern is properly adjusted can
sustainable consumption and hence sustainable development be
achieved, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
