<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Central Bank in $9M Forex Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia in August
recorded a deficit of about nine million U.S. dollars in the
amount of foreign exchange that came into Zambia compared to
outflows.
</P>
<P>
While in-coming foreign exchange amounted to only 2.2 million
dollars, about 10.9 million dollars was spent on outstanding
foreign obligations, leading to a total deficit of 8.7 million
dollars, according to a treasury letter for the month of August
released by Citibank.
</P>
<P>
The amount spent by the central bank on debt-servicing during
the month plunged from 20.7 million dollars in July to 3.5
million dollars, which suggested a reduced capacity to service
debt due to inadequate foreign exchange for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence of the deficit in foreign exchange flows,
Citibank estimates that Zambia's foreign exchange reserves has
declined by eight percent during the month to 105 million
dollars. This means that the Zambian government is approaching
dangerously low levels for maintenance of debt-servicing and
other government operations.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the situation at the central bank, August
statistics on inflows and outflows through commercial banks shows
a surplus of 6.7 million dollars with the consolidated foreign
exchange position increasing to 45.8 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the surplus situation in commercial banks, the
volume of foreign exchange traded dropped by 27 percent to 92
million dollars from July to August, said the newsletter.
</P>
</TEXT>
