<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report Emphasizes Relationship Between Consumption and Human Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Human Development
Report 1998 released this morning emphasized the relationship
between consumption and human development.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Program (UNDP) report, which
was simultaneously released in The Hague and the capitals of more
than 100 countries, focuses on the consumption of goods and
services, and examines whether related trends will promote or
otherwise hinder human progress.
</P>
<P>
The report, which measured human progress and deprivations,
revealed unprecedented growth in consumption during the 20th
century in terms of both scale and diversity. It also pointed out
that the rapid growth of consumption has widened the gap between
the rich and poor.
</P>
<P>
The document showed that a mere 20 percent of the world's
population accounts for some 86 percent of total consumption, and
noted the glaring inequality in consumption opportunities excluded
over one billion people from meeting their basic needs.
</P>
<P>
Canada ranked the first in overall human development for the
fifth consecutive year, with France and Norway following closely
behind in second and third place, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that China's human development index
ranks 106th amongst 174 countries, compared with its ranking of
108th out of 175 countries in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kerstin Leitner, UNDP resident representative in China,
expressed hope that the report will serve as an important
reference for Chinese policy makers, scholars, the media and
external partners for development.
</P>
<P>
She also expressed hope that it will make people think more
about the consumption pattern in China and prompt global society
to aim for the future in order to fulfill the vision centered on
seeking equitable and sustainable consumption.
</P>
<P>
Visiting UN High Commissioner for Human Rights Mary Robinson
said that "China can be commended for its efforts to eliminate
poverty and to meet the basic needs of all citizens."
</P>
<P>
She said she will join the Chinese government in efforts to
ensure the full realization of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Robinson also noted the signing of a memorandum of intent
to promote the development of technical cooperation with China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
