<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Local Oil Firm to Begin Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A local oil company Atlas
Petroleum Nigeria Ltd. is scheduled to begin production in
October this year with a capacity of 15,000 barrels per day
(bpd), raising combined production of local oil companies to
64,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
Atlas Petroleum Nigeria is one of 48 local companies granted
oil prospecting licenses since 1991 when the Nigerian government
introduced an indigenisation program, The Guardian reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Other indigenous oil producers like Nigerian Petroleum
Development company, Dubri Oil, Express Petroleum and
Consolidated Oil have already begun their production.
</P>
<P>
Two others such as Yinka Folawiyo Petroleum and Cavendish
Petroleum are also expected to come on stream before the middle
of next year.
</P>
<P>
The seven-year-old indigenous program implemented by the
Nigerian government is aimed at breaking the monopoly of foreign
companies in the vital oil sector of the country's industry.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is a major oil producing country in the world with a
capacity of 2.5 million bpd mainly produced by multi-national
companies of Shell Petroleum, Mobil Producing, Chevron Nigeria
Ltd. and Elf Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
The growing oil production by local companies may force the
major oil companies to cut down their production to cope with the
quota allowed by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
