<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Releases 21 Detained Minority Youths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian authorities have
released 21 youths of the Ogoni minority groups who have been
held in detention without trial since 1994, in connection with
turmoil in the Ogoni area in south Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Their release was granted Monday by the High Court Seven, Port
Harcourt, Rivers State.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the release, Justice A.C. Woryi said their detention
without trial was unconstitutional, unlawful, illegal, null and void.
He said the release was unconditional.
</P>
<P>
The 21 youths, except Mrs. Daughter Dilosi, who was arrested
in September 1997, were arrested together with nine others
following the turmoil in May 1994, which claimed the lives of
four Ogoni leaders who were said to be pro-governmental.
</P>
<P>
The turmoil was a result of the tension between the government
and the Movement for the Survival of Ogoni People (MOSOP) over
environment protection and community development issues in the
oil-producing Ogoni area.
</P>
<P>
Nine persons, including author Ken Saro-Wiwa were sentenced to
death for murder by a special tribunal and eventually hanged to
death in November 1995, sparking off international sanctions
against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
A statement signed by the State Information Commissioner
Medileine Tador and broadcast over the state radio said the
government released them in the spirit of the national
reconciliation policy of General Abdulsalam Abubakar, who had
ordered the release of all political detainees since his
assumption of office in June.
</P>
<P>
The statement appealed to all Ogoni people to henceforth work
for peace in the state.
</P>
<P>
The release of the 21 persons was confirmed Tuesday morning by
MOSOP's self-exiled leader in London, Ledum Mitee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
