<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Flounder After Wall Street Jumps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
floundered Wednesday in line with weaker Asian markets, despite
Wall Street's biggest ever daily rise on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Australian share market rose sharply at the open but all
gains were wiped out by midday as news hit that the Japanese
market was suffering.
</P>
<P>
A lower Hong Kong market also dampened buying sentiment,
ensuring volumes were kept at modest levels.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 12.7 points softer
at 2542.5, off an intra-day low of 2536.8. In morning trade, it
reached a high of 2581.7.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials slipped 8.0 points to 4472.2 while the
resources index tumbled 19.2 points or 1.9 percent, to 984.8.
</P>
<P>
Resources stocks were mostly lower with giant BHP losing 25
cents to 12.65 Australian dollars and global miner Rio Tinto,
which unveils its interim profit Thursday, slipping 10 cents to
18.40 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks also lost ground as the spot price for bullion was
trading in Sydney 2.90 U.S. dollars per fine ounce cheaper at
284.50 U.S. dollars by late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The gold index forfeited 27.1 points, or 2.65 percent, to
994.8.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks recorded mixed fortunes, with National Australia
Bank rising 22.4 cents to 21.681 Australian dollars, Westpac bank
shedding 18.6 cents to 9.18 Australian dollars, ANZ bank fell nine
cents to 8.72 Australian dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia
closed 12 cents lower at 19.78 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached just 288.03 million shares, worth
894.00 million Australian dollars (525.76 million U.S. dollars),
with falls outpacing rises by 578 to 450 and 358 stocks were
steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
