<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker Under Pressure From Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
Wednesday lower as market focus returned to Asia and the ailing
Japanese banking system.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed the session in Sydney at 58.81 U.S.
cents, from 59.34 U.S. cents on Tuesday night. It traded as low as
58.75 U.S. cents and as high as 59.30 U.S. cents Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nick Volanakis, senior foreign exchange dealer at Colonial
State Bank, said the Australian dollar faced some selling off from
Europe and was starting to see a decline.
</P>
<P>
Volanakis said the U.S. dollar and the Japanese yen had been
affected by the rumors of a derivative loss for Japan's Fuji Bank
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market was swept with rumors the bank had lost
up to three trillion yen on derivatives deals. But the bank was
quick to deny the losses.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar gained a little ground against the
Japanese yen Wednesday to close at 78.66 Japanese yen from 78.48
yen.
</P>
<P>
It was also buying 1.0215 German marks from 1.0276 marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
