<HEADLINE> United Nations to Send Fact-finding Mission to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will send
a fact-finding mission to Afghanistan to determine the fate of the
Iranian diplomats who went missing after the fall of
Mazar-e-Sharif to Taliban troops last month, U.N. sources here
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"(U.N.) Secretary General's office is organizing a mission," an
U.N. official told the Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"You have to contact the Secretary General's office in New
York," the official was quoted as saying when asked about the
composition of the proposed U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
An U.N. spokesman in New York announced Tuesday that Secretary
General Kofi Annan has engaged in discussions regarding the status
of 10 missing Iranian diplomats and a correspondent of the Iranian
official news agency (IRNA).
</P>
<P>
Iran accuses Taliban of holding dozens of its nationals hostage
since capturing Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 km north of Kabul, from
the beleaguered northern alliance.
</P>
<P>
Taliban authorities confirmed that some 40 Iranian drivers were
in their custody but denied that they had detained Iranian
diplomats and IRNA reporter.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban regime last week released five Iranian prisoners as
a mark of good gestures following hectic diplomatic efforts by
Pakistan to stave off possibility of any military confrontation
between the two neighboring Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
Taliban and Iran had agreed on a tripartite mission including
representatives from both sides and Pakistan to visit
Mazar-e-Sharif to look into the matter.
</P>
<P>
Tension escalated between Iran and the Taliban with the
deployment of 70,000 Iranian troops for military exercises along
the Iran and Afghanistan's border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
