<HEADLINE> One More Monk Shot Dead in Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 9 (Xinhua) -- One more monk was shot dead
in clashes between Cambodian police and protesters on Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred demonstrators gathered at the U.S. Embassy to
protest government's crackdown on protesters and Buddhist
monks. They also called on the U.S. to impose sanctions on Hun Sen
and his regime.
</P>
<P>
When riot police tried to disperse the demonstrators, clashes
burst into violence. One Buddist monk was shot dead and an AP
press photographer seriously injured in the head.
</P>
<P>
At least three protesters, including two monks and one cycle
driver have been killed and scores of others injured since
September 7.
</P>
<P>
King Norodom Sihanouk Tuesday said he was "saddened to receive
the news about the deaths and injuries of the monks and Buddhist
people, which make me worried."
</P>
<P>
Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy, leaders of two main
opposition parties strongly condemned the violence.
</P>
<P>
They also vowed that they would never participate in the new
National Assembly (parliament) and the government before the
election fraud was resolved and the violence against the
protesters stopped.
</P>
<P>
They added they believed that the international community would
never accept and assist a new government which is formed by
force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
