<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skin Cancer May Signal Other Cancers, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, September 8 (Xinhua) -- A study released Tuesday
said people with non-melanoma skin cancers had about 25 percent
higher annual risk of death from other cancers compared to persons
who did not have skin cancer at all.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by researchers at Emory University and the
American Cancer Society and published in the September 9th issue
of The Journal of the American Medical Association, focused on the
1982-1994 health outcomes of more than 1.1 million adults taking
part in the Cancer Prevention Study II. Nearly 48,000 study
subjects died of cancer during the 12 years.
</P>
<P>
The researchers found that men and women with non-melanoma
skin cancer faced increased risks for lung cancer (up 37 percent
for men, 46 percent for women), and non-Hodgkin lymphoma (32
percent for men, 50 percent for women).
</P>
<P>
Men with non-melanoma skin cancers had increased risks for
cancers of the testes (12 times the risk) and salivary glands (3
times the risk), as well as increased risk of prostate cancer (27
percent), bladder cancer (41 percent), and leukemia (37 percent).
</P>
<P>
Women with a previous history of non-melanoma skin cancer was
associated with 34 percent increase in their long-term risk of
developing breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said right now they do not know the reasons
behind all these associations, speculating that the increased
exposure to ultraviolet sunlight that can trigger skin cancers
might also have a role to play in the development of other cancers.
</P>
<P>
"If the common link between these cancers is ultraviolet light,
then taking steps to reduce the risk of skin cancer would also
help reduce risk of other cancers," said Michael Thun, a cancer
society researcher who co-authored the study.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
