<HEADLINE> Israel Pledges to Work out Deal with Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official on
Wednesday pledged Israel's determination to work towards striking
a redeployment deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Danny Naveh, personal envoy of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu who arrived here earlier in the morning, made the pledge
following talks with President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
In a short meeting with reporters, Naveh said he "updated" the
Egyptian leader on the recent negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinians on the long-overdue second Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
For the past six months, Israel has been resisting an American
initiative calling for a 13 percent Israeli pullback. The
Palestinians had already accepted the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Naveh indicated that Netanyahu has made up his mind to reach a
deal with the Palestinians on the U.S. idea. "The prime minister
is ready to do all he can to reach an agreement with the
Palestinians based on reciprocity," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to go back to negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here still doubt if a deal is really around the
corner, for Netanyahu has repeatedly declared that Israel and the
Palestinians are "near, very near" an agreement.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's political advisor, Osama el-Baz, on the other hand,
told reporters that Mubarak gave the Israeli envoy "some advices"
as to "what Israel's position should be" during the talks.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that a failure in the peace talks would lead to
instability in the region and no party should apply pressure on
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
According to Egyptian press, Israel has been accusing Cairo of
trying to obstruct an Israeli-Palestinian agreement, because it
repeated that any deal has to be fair and balanced, instead of
sacrificing the interest of either party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
