<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian, NZ Breast Implant Victims to Get </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 4,000 Australian
and New Zealand women stand to receive up to 125,000 Australian
dollars (75,000 U.S. dollars) each under a compensation payout for
injury from silicone breast implants, the Australian Associated
Press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for the women said Wednesday U.S. company Dow Corning
has reached an in-principle agreement to pay 39.5 million U.S.
dollars to settle Australian and New Zealand claims against it,
the wire service said in a report released from Brisbane, capital
of the state of Queensland, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement represents a victory for the women who have
fought a seven-year battle for compensation for the pain and
disease they claim have been inflicted from the implants.
</P>
<P>
Law firm Slater and Gordon said the deal is far better than
anything previously offered and would deliver more money, more
quickly than any other option.
</P>
<P>
Most claims should be paid within three years.
</P>
<P>
However, while claimant Gail Jackson said the likely payout
would be "very nice," it would hardly reimburse her for the pain
and suffering caused by implants over 26 years.
</P>
<P>
Paula Shelton, from Slater and Gordon, said the Australia-New
Zealand deal is one of the first foreign settlements to be made
with Dow Corning, which is facing claims by more than 170,000
women around the world.
</P>
<P>
She said the agreement would ensure that women receive their
compensation within seven years under a U.S. bankruptcy plan being
approved, with most waiting no longer than three years.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Bankruptcy Court has been overseeing compensation
payouts since Dow Corning filed for bankruptcy protection in 1995,
enabling it to close off liabilities and continue to trade.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of women claim to have suffered auto-immune and
connective disorders as a result of silicone implants, 80 percent
of which were for cosmetic purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
