<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liupan Mountain Emerges as Green Island on Loess Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A barren mountain 40 years
ago, Liupan Mountain in northwest China is now nearly covered with
trees, and has emerged as a green island on the loess plateau.
</P>
<P>
The annual rainfall on the mountain located in the Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region exceeds 700 millimeters, and the mountain now
plays a vital role in water and soil conservation for the loess
plateau, where average rainfall is 300 millimeters overall.
</P>
<P>
Located over 400 kilometers south of Yinchuan, the regional
capital, Liupan Mountain covers an area of about 70,000 hectares
and is surrounded by the loess plateau.
</P>
<P>
According to Lin Jianguo, deputy director of the Liupan
Mountain Forest Administrative Bureau, the mountain had turned
desolate by the end of 1950s due to human destruction and a
worsening environment, but has been saved by enhanced forest
protection measures in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, the mountain was designated by the state as a national
nature reserve. At present, the mountain's forest reserve
encompasses 1.5 million cubic meters, and is increasing at an
annual rate of 270,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Liupan Mountain is home to 788 plant varieties and 213 animal
species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: SADC Summit to Dwell on Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Ma Guihua)
</P>
<P>
GRAND BAIE (Mauritius), September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Southern
African Development Community (SADC) summit due to open here on
September 13-14 will again dwell on the political crisis in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Angola.
</P>
<P>
The summit will be briefed by heads of state or government
from the DRC, Angola and Lesotho on developments in their
countries and examine possible long-term solutions to the
political problems in these countries, said SADC Executive
Secretary Kaire Mbuende Monday in his preview of the meeting in
the Mauritian resort of Grand Baie.
</P>
<P>
The DRC, which joined the regional grouping last year, has
seen much turbulence in the past month when the Tutsi-led
Banyamulenge rebels took up arms against Laurent Kabila's
15-month old government.
</P>
<P>
The fighting soon spread from the east of the third biggest
African country to its west, with three other SADC members,
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia, pouring in troops and arms to help
prop up the Kabila government.
</P>
<P>
The 14 SADC member states have thus been divided in their
approaches to the Congo crisis, with those led by South Africa
advocating for diplomatic solutions whereas Zimbabwe and some of
its allies are in for military intervention.
</P>
<P>
But South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki denied any
differences between his government and Zimbabwe over the
Congolese issue at the 12th Non-Aligned Movement summit in South
Africa's east port city of Durban earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
"Both countries want a cease-fire immediately. Both countries
want a withdrawal of foreign troops," said Mbeki.
</P>
<P>
In Angola, the faltering peace process has been stranded as
the opposition movement National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) failed to fully comply with the 1994 Lusaka Peace
Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The recent announcement by the Angolan government to expel
UNITA members from the government of national unity and the
parliament has led to discrepancies within the former rebel UNITA
movement, with some of the expelled ministers and MPs voicing to
defect their leader Jonas Savimbi who they said is more
interested in war than peace.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the increasing rivalry between the Angolan
government and the UNITA might trigger off yet another civil war
in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, the summit will review the performance
of member states in the past twelve months as well as examine the
negative impact of the Asian and Russian financial crisis on the
region's economies.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will evaluate both national and regional
strategies being put in place to ensure financial stability and
continued socio-economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The SADC heads of state and government will also receive an
updated report on the food security situation against the
background of erratic and below-normal rainfall in some of the
southern African countries and excessive rains and flooding in
other parts of the region such as Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Production forecasts in the region indicate a decline of about
six percent in maize harvest of 16.10 million tons against last
year's 17.05 million tons, which will also be noted during the
summit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the region has an overall cereal deficit of 510,000
tons, a shortfall of 1.35 million tons of millet, according to
the SADC executive secretary.
</P>
<P>
The summit is also expected to consider new protocols for
signature relating to tourism, facilitation of free movement of
peoples in the community and the establishment of the SADC
Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
A Statement on Violence Against Women and Children; a
Convention Against Corruption and a Declaration on the Status of
Refugees in the region are also on the cards.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, the most influential organization in southern Africa
which was established in 1992, now comprises Angola, Botswana,
the DRC, Lesotho, Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia,
Seychelles, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
A three-day meeting of the SADC Standing Committee of
Officials and a two-day Council of Ministers conference will be
held before the annual summit proceeds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
