<HEADLINE> Israeli-Turkish Jets to Hold First Joint Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli and Turkish air
forces are to hold a first joint air maneuver in Israel from
September 13 to 18, the Jerusalem Post newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report did not say how many Turkish jet fighters would take
part in the exercises, the first since the two countries signed a
military cooperation agreement in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Jet fighters from the two countries have trained in each
other's airspace over the past two years, but they have never
flown together.
</P>
<P>
A squadron of Turkish F-16s was in Israel last June to receive
training on testing grounds jointly-run by Israel Air Force (IAF)
and Rafael, the Armaments Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
The IAF and Rafael have put together an "Air Combat
Maneuvering Instrumentation Range" in the Negev desert, south
Israel, where the jets trained to evade surface-to-air missiles,
possibly similar to the Russian S-300 anti-aircraft missiles Greek
Cypriots plan to deploy in November to balance Turkish air
superiority over the Island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974, when Turkey landed
troops on the island and took over the northern third in the wake
of an abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Turkey also planed to conduct another joint naval
maneuver in November this year. The maneuver, called Reliant
Mermaid II, is a continuation of last January's Reliant Mermaid I,
allegedly for search and rescue purposes.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan would again be invited to participate in the
new naval exercises, as they were for January.
</P>
<P>
The January's naval exercises were condemned by Egypt, but
Jordan sent an observer aboard the Turkish ship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
