<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Revise National Security Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung Wednesday said his government will revise the National
Security Law to take out items which violate human rights.
</P>
<P>
It will not be long before the revision is made, Kim said when
he met Pierre Sane, Secretary-General of Amnesty International,
who arrived here for a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kim said that he will never abuse the security law
to prolong his power.
</P>
<P>
During the 15th presidential race last December, Kim Dae-jung,
then opposition candidate, said he would revise the law after he
became president of the country.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, President Kim, who was regarded as a prisoner
of conscience by the Amnesty International during the military
governments, told Sane that he agrees, in principle, with Amnesty
International's campaign to abolish death penalty worldwide.
</P>
<P>
But the president did not say whether his government will scrap
capital punishment in South Korea as there has yet been no debate
on abolition of death penalty in the country, said presidential
spokesman Park Jie-won.
</P>
<P>
Kim said he is interested in considering the possibility of
releasing political prisoners when the Amnesty International
secretary-general asked whether Kim will set free the remaining
political prisoners, many of whom have been behind bars for nearly
40 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
