<HEADLINE> China Urges Teachers to Update Methodology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Education
issued an open letter today urging teachers nationwide to update
outdated instructional methodology in order to improve student
creativity.
</P>
<P>
The letter points out that the next century will represent a
new information age featuring a high technology revolution which
will influence the entire world. Meeting new challenges require
adjustments in China's traditional educational theories and
methods.
</P>
<P>
China's Teachers have for thousands of years been affected by
doctrines in which Confucius defined teachers as fountains of
knowledge and reliable sources of information. Students have, in
fact, been required to believe everything put forward by their
teachers.
</P>
<P>
The letter refers to the tradition as a "duck-feeding" model
which detracts from the independence and creativity of students.
</P>
<P>
"Teachers should change role as simply instructors to guides,
and students should become more actively involved in the learning
process," according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
It stresses that teachers should enaged in self-improvement,
and notes that the ministry is currently devising a related
reeducation program.
</P>
<P>
China celebrates Teachers Day on September 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
