<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Great Opportunities Await Infrastructure Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Enlarged expenditures this
year provides great opportunities for companies dealing with
public utilities, project contracting and real estate development,
according to some of China's stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
Companies in these three sectors can expect steady business
growth during the second half of the year, as the national economy
turns stronger as a result of the government's stimulation
policies, predicted analysts with the Shenyin-Wanguo Securities
Co. Ltd., the largest in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has emphasized on increasing investment
demand this year to offset the impact of waning export trade and
consumer demand, two other major national economic factors, in the
wake of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Economists have projected gross investment in infrastructure at
about one trillion yuan for this year, which are expected to go
mainly into infrastructure, including construction of bridges,
highways, urban utilities, water conservation and environmental
protection projects, industries using new and high technologies,
technical renovations in state enterprises, and real estate
development.
</P>
<P>
"The huge investment demand created by the government is
expected to provide great market potential for companies in
public utilities, project contracting, and real estate sector,"
said a stock analyst with Shenyin-Wanguo Securities.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure sector is already receiving a good share of
the money. To cite an example, the Ministry of Finance issued 100
billion yuan worth of special treasury bonds on September 4 for
infrastructure projects, demanding another 100 billion yuan in
credit support from commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Companies in related industries maintained growth momentum
during the January-June period. Public utility companies, for
example, reported an average growth of 30 percent in business
volume and 50 percent in net profit.
</P>
<P>
Hi-tech firms are also expected to register higher growth
during the second half, according to some stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
Economic recovery depends heavily on such companies, and they
have already registered an average net profit growth of more than
20 percent during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
By the same analysis, companies manufacturing machinery,
household electric appliances, chemicals, and the power industry
are expected to come out of their current predicament as the
national economy starts to recover.
</P>
<P>
Also, importers may enjoy a turn for the better during the
later half of the year as a result of increasing import volume.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
