<HEADLINE> Philippine President Backs Probe of Human Organ Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Wednesday hailed proposals to conduct a congressional
probe into the alleged murder of overseas Filipino workers by an
international syndicate and the sale of their vital internal
organs.
</P>
<P>
"The president will support all efforts to unmask the leaders
and members of this syndicate. A congressional inquiry may unearth
vital information that will help the government put a stop to this
despicable racket," Press Undersecretary Lcasiano Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
Quzon City House representative Dante Liban Tuesday filed a
resolution for a joint inquiry by the foreign and labor committees
of the House of Representatives into the alleged report. The
resolution is supported by some congressmen.
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez said the president is determined to stop these
"depraved and abominable" crimes and bring to justice their
perpetrators, adding that Estrada wants "the full might of the
government thrown against these criminals."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippine government is also mounting a
crackdown on illegal recruiters of overseas Filipino workers, the
alleged partner of the international syndicate.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada ordered law enforcement agencies along with
the Philippine Overseas Employment Administration and the Overseas
Workers Welfare Administration to make aggressive efforts to
unmask and bring to justice the illegal recruiters.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also ordered the concerned departments to launch a
massive information campaign in the provinces so that those
planning to seek employment abroad could be forewarned against
dealing with the illegal recruiters.
</P>
<P>
"President Estrada considers illegal recruitment as a crime
more heinous than kidnapping because it victimizes the poor whose
dream to give their children a better life ultimately ends in
tragedy in foreign lands," Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has about 6 million overseas contract workers
in more than 100 countries and regions. It was reported that every
day there is at least one death of overseas Filipino workers for
various reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
