<HEADLINE> Sight First In Action In Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Over one thousand cataract
patients in the Tibet Autonomous Region are expected to regain
their eyesight within a month, thanks to a state-sponsored medical
team that is providing free surgery in the region.
</P>
<P>
As part of Sight First China Action launched in 1997 by the
Ministry of Health, the Chinese Disabled Persons Federation and
Lions Club International, the team began working in Tibet on
August 25 and has so far performed 340 operations on local
cataract sufferers.
</P>
<P>
Due to high altitudes and excessive exposure to ultraviolet
rays, Tibetans have a cataract incident rate double that of other
parts of the country. Yet most counties and townships in Tibet are
without ophthalmological hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the medical workers are touring four prefectures in
the region though seasonal flood waters have brought many
difficulties and inconveniences to their endeavor.
</P>
<P>
China has some four million cataract patients, and Sight First
China Action has pledged to cure 1.75 million of them by the year
2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Grain Reserves Intact from Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Grain reserves in northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province, an area known as the nation's major
rice bowl, have remained basically intact in spite the most severe
flooding recorded this century.
</P>
<P>
The province's 700-odd grainaries have a combined storage
capacity of 25.8 million tons. Heavy flood waters which threatened
grain reserves of over 3.55 million tons are slowly receding, and
the security of an additional 3.5 million tons is now guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
"Strong support for the province's flood relief efforts has
contributed greatly to maintaining a stable grain market,"
according to a provincial official in charge of grain reserve.
</P>
<P>
He added that the success can be largely attributed to the
substantial manpower and massive funding devoted to protecting
state grain reserves.
</P>
<P>
The Xindian grain depot was virtually an intact island during
the flooding, with strengthened levees holding back flood waters
rising as much as two meters above ground level.
</P>
<P>
The city of Tongjiang raised 2.29 million yuan, including
provincial government funding, over a 10 day period to extend
levees by some 5,700 meters in order to adequately protect two
threatened grain depots.  
</P>
</TEXT>
