<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Largest National Park Planned for Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Tourism departments from China
and the United States will join hands to build the world's largest
national park in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The park will cover 66,800 sq.km. in 15 counties in the
northwestern prefectures of Lijiang, Diqing, Dali and Nujiang. The
region is located south of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Three major rivers -- Jinsha, Lancang and Nujiang -- will flow
through the park for distances ranging from 70 km to over 3,000
kilometers. The park will offer rare natural scenery and will be
the world's Top Ten regions in terms of biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
The development plan is being prepared and experts note the
park will promote the development of tourism and aid the local
poverty alleviation program.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan enjoys abundant tourism resources and vast development
potential. The province ranked 7th in the nation with over 805,400
foreign tourists in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Top on China's Resource Shortage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- A shortage in forest coverage
is now the number one natural resource problem in China, according
to the State Forestry Administration (SFA).
</P>
<P>
A report released today by the SFA said that green coverage per
capita in China is now only 11.7 percent of the world's average.
</P>
<P>
"With a coverage of 13.92 percent, forest shortage is even more
severe than other resource-related problems, such as water, arable
land and mining resource," the report said, adding that the
shortage of forest has caused a series of economic, social and
environmental problems to the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, soil erosion covers 3.67 million
square kilometers, or 38 percent of China's land area. This figure
continues to grow at a rate of 2,460 square kilometers per year.
</P>
<P>
Six major cities including Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou are
now listed among the ten most polluted cities in the world, the
report said, adding that this is to some extent related to lack of
greenery in Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the increasing incidence of natural
disasters in China in recent decades is largely caused by the
forest shortage.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, China was hit 70 percent more by natural
disasters than in the 1970s, and 110 percent more than in the
1950s, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
