<HEADLINE> Philippines Handles Financial Crisis Well: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has praised the
Philippines for handling well the ongoing Asian financial crisis
and expressed optimism about the country's future economy,
Presidential Spokesman Fernando Barican said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The policy response of the Philippine government to the crisis
situation has, on the whole, been appropriate and the Philippines
is correctly perceived by investors at home and abroad as having
weathered the crisis better than many of its neighbors," World
Bank country director Vinay Bhargava was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's meeting with President Joseph Estrada at the
Presidential Palace, Bhargava also expressed full confidence in
the Philippines' capability to sustain economic growth despite the
fact that the financial crisis is getting worse, Barican said.
</P>
<P>
He said Bhargava informed the president that "the prospects are
good" for the Philippines to achieve 1 percent growth in the gross
domestic product in 1998, and 3.5 percent in 1999 and over 5
percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Bhargava said the World Bank would help the country revive its
economy by, among other measures, restructuring the
2.6-billion-U.S.-dollar portfolio of ongoing projects and quickly
approving about 1 billion dollars in new loans to the Philippines.
 
</P>
