<HEADLINE> Jordan Silent on Reported Talks with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government has
refrained from commenting on media reports that its intelligence
chief was in Israel last week for talks on forming a military
alliance with Turkey and Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We do not usually comment on the movement of our security
officers," said Minister of Information Nasir Judeh, quoted by the
semi-official Jordan Times newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Ma'ariv newspaper had reported that Samih Batikhi,
Jordan's top intelligence officer, held talks on Sunday with
senior Israeli intelligence and military officers on the prospect
of building the three-way alliance.
</P>
<P>
However, Judeh reiterated Jordan's position of rejecting "the
concept of alliances and pacts," adding that "our approach to
security in the region is comprehensive, inclusive of all and
exclusive of none."
</P>
<P>
Jordan has bilateral security arrangements with both Turkey
and Israel and plans to beef up military cooperation with Ankara
next year. Tel Aviv and Ankara have signed a couple of defense
pacts and enjoy close military ties.
</P>
<P>
Arab states are concerned about the growing cooperation among
the three parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
