<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Hails China As Good Investment Example </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 9 (Xinhua) --China is the most successful
example of absorbing direct foreign investment among all
developing countries, said a senior U.N. official here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rubens Ricupero, secretary-general of the U.N. Conference on
Trade and Development(UNCTD), made the remark at a news
conference, referring to the fact that the flow of direct overseas
funding into China has undergone an unprecedented increase in the
past six years.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero is here for the Second China Fair for International
Investment and Trade. He said that China acquired total direct
investments of 45 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, about half the sum
for all of Asia.
</P>
<P>
That figure is also twice the total volume of foreign
investment in Africa, and central and east Europe, and accounted
for 11 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
Ricupero expressed confidence in the prospects for direct
investment in China, citing China's economic conditions, business
convenience and policy framework.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that financial opportunism such as that sweeping
some Latin American countries will never happen in China.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced the belief that the Asian financial crisis will
not have much effect on overall direct investment. According to a
world-wide survey conducted by the UNCTD, most of the world's top
500 companies have no intention of postponing or cancelling direct
investment in southeast Asia, and most of them even plan to
increase such funding. Those which have having reduced investment
account for fewer than ten percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
