<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trains to Run Faster in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- China's railway departments
are going all out to consolidate railroad tracks, bridges,
crossings, signals, and telecommunication facilities in
preparation for higher speeds which will begin on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Fly-overs have been built on rail crossings on lines with
speeds exceeding 140 km per hour, and high-speed lines will be
fenced off in the future, a ministry official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Trains with speeds of 140-to-160 kilometers per hour will run
on three key lines linking Beijing with Guangzhou, Shanghai, and
Harbin. Train speeds will also be raised on railway lines from
Hangzhou to Zhuzhou, Houma to Yueshan, Baoji to Zhongwei, Nanning
to Kunming, and Wuwei to Urumqi.
</P>
<P>
Tests on the Beijing-Kowloon railway show that the journey from
Beijing to Shenzhen will require only 24 hours, 11 hours shorter
than current travel time.
</P>
<P>
A high-speed train also will soon be introduced on the
Guangzhou-Shenzhen line capable of maintaining speeds up to 200
kilometers per hour under existing track conditions.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Ministry of Railways will increase the number
of fast trains, overnight trains and daytime trains, and arrange
more special trains for tourists, non-local workers and football
fans.
</P>
<P>
Railway transport has been challenged by express highways and
civil aviation in recent years. Faster trains are just one way
railway departments have adopted to sharpen their
competitiveness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
