<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Activate Standby Loan Program with IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Central Bank Governor Gabriel
Singson said here Wednesday that the Philippines is activating a
standby loan program with the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
which will enable the country to draw 13.5 billion U.S. dollars
from IMF.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the country can draw the first tranche of 260
million dollars by October 23 if the economic review report made
by an IMF panel is approved by the IMF Executive Board.
</P>
<P>
The panel visited the Philippines from August 20 to September 8
and held a number of discussions with Philippine economic
managers. Both parties agreed on a revised economic program for
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Among the major revisions are the gross national product (GNP),
the gross domestic product (GDP), inflation and balance of
payments projections.
</P>
<P>
Singson repeated that the GNP targets have been cut to 1.5
percent for 1998 and 4.1 percent for 1999 while the GDP targets
have been revised downward to 1 percent and 3.5 percent for the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
Drawing on the IMF facility would allow the Philippines to have
enough foreign exchange reserve to combat speculative attacks on
the local currency of peso and help rebuild the economy battered
by the Asian financial crisis, economists said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines and the IMF agreed on the standby loan program
in April this year in case that the country's financial situation
would suddenly get worse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
