<HEADLINE> 25 People Die of Cholera in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- At least 25 people died of
cholera in Iran by Tuesday morning, and thousands more are
infected, the Zan (Women) newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reza Qasemi, director general for preventive affairs in the
Health Ministry, told the daily that so far 3,290 people have been
infected with the disease throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that most patients were in the four provinces of
Tehran, Isfahan, Qom, and Sistan and Baluchestan.
</P>
<P>
Qasemi believed that main reason behind the widespread of the
disease this year was hot weather and excessive rain in these
areas.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that hygiene education would be the basic way to
prevent further incidences.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Health Minister Ali Akbar Sayari, cholera
last hit Iran in 1997, when more than 1,100 people were infected.
</P>
</TEXT>
