<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Expected to Sell More State-Owned Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 9 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny Shipley has signaled further sales of state-owned assets and
government spending cuts after the National Party-led minority
government won a confidence vote in Parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Shipley Wednesday told the Evening Post, a Wellington-based
newspaper, that the confidence vote gave the government "some
clear air" to advance its policy program, including privatization.
As well, in response to the country's economic downturn and
forecast budget deficits, the government would also look closely
at its proposed spending.
</P>
<P>
According to a Treasury Forecast, which was submitted to the
Parliament Tuesday, the unemployment rate in New Zealand will rise
to 8.5 percent early next year from the current 7.7 percent, the
economic growth will fall by 0.5 percent in the year ending March
1999, and the government accounts will be plunged into the red in
the years of 1999-2000 and 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said that the only way to turn around looming deficits
is to cut spending or adopt measures to boost economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"We will look at both sides of that ledger," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Treasury forecasts were based on current government policy,
she said, adding that the government now has to look at projected
spending programs and decide which would be continued, which would
be delayed and which would be canceled.
</P>
<P>
Selling assets would also help the government through a
difficult period. Money from sales would add to the operating
balance of the government and allow it to continue repaying debt,
she noted.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said she expects some state-owned assets, which have
been rated as "strategic assets," would be sold.
</P>
<P>
She made it clear that she prefers privatization, saying
private owners are better able to make the capital investment
companies need.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
