<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Leaves for Egypt on Official Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri left here Wednesday for Cairo on a three-day official visit
to Egypt, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, accompanied by four cabinet ministers and other senior
government officials, will focus his talks with Egyptian leaders
on bilateral ties, especially economic cooperation, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Cairo, Hariri will co-chair with his
Egyptian counterpart Kamal El-Ganzouri the third session of the
Lebanese-Egyptian Higher Committee which was first kicked off in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will sign an agreement on the establishment of a
free trade zone between the two countries and discuss the
possibility of organizing trade fairs in both countries.
</P>
<P>
In the projected free trade zone, customs duties on
agricultural and industrial products of the two countries will be
reduced systematically and annually so that they will be totally
eliminated within five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has concluded similar agreements with Morocco and
Tunisia and will soon do so with Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Bahrain
as a prelude to setting up an Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Egypt and Lebanon rose to 74 million U.S. dollars
in 1997, of which 58 million dollars are Egyptian exports to
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hariri will also discuss the long-stalled Middle East peace
process and regional affairs with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and Secretary-general of the
Arab League Ismat Abdel Meguid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
