<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Predicts More Diabetes Cases in Developing Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of diabetes
sufferers in developing nations will rise to 228 million in 2025,
170 percent up from 1995, warned a new study on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure for industrialized nations will be 72 million in
2025, 42 percent more than 1995, said the study conducted by a
team of researchers of the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
They predicted the disease will become more prevalent among people
living in urban areas and among the middle-aged in developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the September issue of the journal,
Diabetes Care, listed obesity as one of the factors that increased
the risk of contracting the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
