<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Sets to Achieve 11 Percent Growth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Shandong Province, one of the
economic powerhouses in east China, has been striving for an
annual growth of 11 percent to help the country fulfil its target
of 8 percent, which has been threatened by the devastating floods
this summer.
</P>
<P>
Despite the adverse impact of the Asian financial turmoil and
weak domestic market demand, the province realized 324 billion
yuan in gross domestic product (GDP) in the first half of the
year, up 10.3 percent from the same period of 1997, and 3.3
percent more than the national average.
</P>
<P>
"We are ensuring a yearly growth rate of 9 percent, and aiming at 11
percent," said provincial Governor Li Chunting.
</P>
<P>
In the remaining months of the year, the province will inject
221 billion yuan into fixed assets, 23 percent higher than last
year, to stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Much of these funds will go into rural infrastructure to
promote agricultural industrialization and the rapid development of
village and township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The province will also pursue healthier and more efficient
industrial growth focused on improving the management of some 130
key enterprises and enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
Shandong also intends to step up efforts to turn its
non-government businesses and the service sector into new growth
areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Maritime Environment Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is
making great efforts to protect its maritime environment, not only
to curb maritime pollution, but also for the strategic development
and utilization of marine resources.
</P>
<P>
The serious pollution in China's Bohai Sea, for example, has
become a major issue brought to the attention of the government
and experts.
</P>
<P>
Ding Dewen, a scholar at the Chinese Academy of Engineering,
warns that pollutants in the Bohai Sea has caused a sharp drop in
marine organisms, and deterioration of the marine environment
could turn the Bohai Sea into a "dead sea."
</P>
<P>
The region around the Bohai Sea is filled with developed
economies, concentrated cities and townships, and flourishing
industries. However, the sea is suffering from pollution
discharges from a large number of sources, including rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Sea, with a water area of 77,000 square kilometers,
accounts for only 1.6 percent of China's four sea areas, but it is
inflicted with 32 percent of the total waste water, and 47 percent
of all pollutants, discharged into China's seas.
</P>
<P>
Chinese marine experts have suggested that a special committee
be set up to promote protection of the Bohai Sea. They also
suggested that a law on Bohai Sea environmental protection be
adopted, and a Bohai Sea ecological improvement pilot zone be
established.
</P>
<P>
Provinces, cities and enterprises along the Bohai Sea have
already taken a series of measures to reduce pollution of its
waters.
</P>
<P>
The cleaning up of polluting sources on land and centralized
disposal of waste water are the two major steps China has taken to
deal with waste water.
</P>
<P>
The region along the Bohai Sea is not the only
example. Provinces and cities along the country's coastline also
pour huge amount of money into fighting sea pollution.
</P>
<P>
The four cities of Dalian, Qingdao, Yantai and Shanghai have
invested 10 billion yuan into controlling water pollution.
</P>
<P>
Other efforts include closing polluting enterprises and
establishing sewage treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has clearly stipulated that all
enterprises should discharge their pollutants within the standard
set by the state by year 2000 by establishing sewage treatment
facilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0227 </DOCNO>
