<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet to Boost Fishery Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Tibet has adopted new measures
to speed up its development of fish breeding.
</P>
<P>
The local government will provide special funds to build a
number of fish farms and aquatic products processing facilities in
suburban areas of several cities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is striving for an annual aquatic products output of
1,900 tons in year 2000, 250 tons more than that of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Though the land-locked region is far from the sea, it is the
source of many major rivers, and its salt lakes are rich in
insects that serve as quality food for shrimp and crab. Tibet also
has more than 70 fish species.
</P>
<P>
The region will lease more uncultivated wet lands to farmers
for fish breeding.
</P>
<P>
Banks are also required to offer more loans to those promising
to start up fish breeding projects.
</P>
<P>
The region will also open a number of service centers to spread
fish-breeding techniques to all the cities and prefectures in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
