<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Sri Lanka in Coast Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has provided
Sri Lanka with a further 50 million rupees (7.58 million U.S.
dollars) for the second phase of a coast conservation project by
preventing sea erosion, bank sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank made this move after considering Sri Lanka's progress
in the ongoing coast conservation activities, the sources told
Xinhua by telephone.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, sea erosion will be prevented by laying
boulders on the coastal belt. At present the first phase of this
project has already been completed during which the bank has
provided 100 million rupees (15.2 million dollars), the sources
added.
</P>
<P>
Sea erosion, particularly along the southern coast, has become
a major problem for Sri Lanka where several miles of coastline
have been eroded in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The erosion has been mainly attributed to illegal coral mining.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
