<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Rejects Unconditional Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has declared that she would never have unconditional
talks with the rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam
(LTTE), the official Daily News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Kurunegala District Convention in North Central
Province Tuesday evening, Kumaratunga referred to demands by
opposition leader Ranil Wickremesinghe and LTTE representative
Thamil Chelvam that the government negotiate with the LTTE without
conditions.
</P>
<P>
She insinuated that there was a tie-up between the opposition
and the LTTE and stressed that one of the main conditions for
talks is that the country should remain undivided.
</P>
<P>
By calling for unconditional talks the opposition leader was
asking for the division of the country, she said.
</P>
<P>
The president also said there was understanding between the
LTTE and the United National Party to work together with the aim
of toppling the People's Alliance government.
</P>
<P>
She said that if the opposition does not support the
government, she would go direct to the people and get their
support to bring peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga won the 1994 elections on a pledge to establish
peace through negotiation and immediately launched unconditional
talks with the LTTE. However the LTTE rebels reneged on the peace
talks and resumed their war against the government.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga has demanded that the LTTE lay down arms for any
negotiations with her government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
