<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Senator Clears Misconceptions About Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Many Italians and other
Westerners have profound misconceptions about Tibet, said Italian
Senator Renzo Gubert.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua after a recent trip to
Tibet, Gubert pointed out that the misconceptions have hindered
these people from understanding correctly the tremendous
development of the Chinese autonomous region over the past decades.
</P>
<P>
A five-member Italian parliamentary delegation including Gubert
visited Tibet from August 21 to 31 at the invitation of the
Chinese Association for International Understanding.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is stable and its people there enjoy broad religious
freedom and a happy life. The exploitation and social unequality
that existed when Tibet was ruled under the serf system have been
eliminated, said Gubert.
</P>
<P>
The allegation that Tibetans do not have religious freedom is
totally untrue, said the senator.
</P>
<P>
Gubert said he was told by the Tibetan locals that the central
government of China or the local government of the autonomous
region never interfere with their religious freedom except during
the chaotic Cultural Revolution era from 1966 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan lamas he met said it is one's own choice to be or
not to be a lama.
</P>
<P>
Gubert said that Tibetan culture is well protected and it is
absolutely untrue that Tibetan culture has suffered irreparable
destruction.
</P>
<P>
China has made great efforts to protect and maintain the
numerous monasteries.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan language is being taught in all schools in the
autonomous region, said the senator.
</P>
<P>
China, which carries out one-child policy to curb the booming
population, allows Tibetans to have two or more children, said
Gubert.
</P>
<P>
The senator said the members of the delegation he led have
decided to hold a press conference in Rome about what they
saw and felt during the Tibet trip in an effort to remove the
misconceptions of some people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
