<HEADLINE> Japan Gives Sri Lanka Loan for Water Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
granted a soft loan of 93 million U.S. dollars to Sri Lanka for a
water project in the greater Colombo area, Water Supply Department
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project, the Kalu Ganga project, is expected to give
standard water supply to residents who have had problems such as
unclean water from pipe mains, tube wells without water and
low-pressure pipelines, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to fulfill the water requirements of the areas
in the south of greater Colombo using the Kalu Ganga River as its
source.
</P>
<P>
A water purification station that can produce 13.5 million
gallons a day will also be set up under the project, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Some areas in south Colombo at present are supplied with water
only seven hours a day. When the new scheme comes into operation
the areas will have 24-hour supply, the officials said, adding
that areas with low-pressure pipe mains will also benefit.
</P>
