<HEADLINE> Flood Situation May Worsen in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The flood situation in
Bangladesh may take an alarming turn in the central districts
including the capital city of Dhaka in the next three to four
days, according to the Flood Forecasting and Warning Center.
</P>
<P>
The center sent a special alert signal Tuesday night to the top
authorities, saying the situation in and around Dhaka city "needs
special attention from all corners" as the flood there might
assume a serious proportion, press reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Narayangaj District, 16 kilometers southeast of here, the
administration Tuesday started looking for ways to evacuate people
in case the 34-kilometer-long Dhaka-Narayangaj-Demra embankment
collapses.
</P>
<P>
Breaches have developed at 36 points of the dam and the water
level is rising further threatening the embankment, the reports
added.
</P>
<P>
In the event of an evacuation, the district administration has
asked the army, police and Red Crescent volunteers to participate
in the effort.
</P>
<P>
All efforts are being made to save the embankment, which
protects some 600,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Roads and Highways Department officials and employees were
working round the clock to save the embankment, which became most
vulnerable at three points, the Press Information Department said
in a press release Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The current devastating flood, which began early July when the
monsoon season started in the country, has affected nearly 30
million people in 47 of the country's 64 districts, with the
flood-related death toll rising to 631 so far, according to the
Control Room of the Relief Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
