<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Progress Made in Talks With DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that some progress has been made in talks with the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on several issues.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters that
issues on which progress were made included the 1994 U.S.-DPRK
agreement, missile proliferation, terrorism and a resumption of
talks aimed at reducing tensions and achieving a lasting peace on
the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said U.S. and DPRK negotiators who met in New York last
week have returned to their capitals for consultations. And
Washington was also consulting with its allies, including South
Korea and Japan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Pentagon said the United States was continuing
to investigate DPRK's claim that it launched a satellite into
orbit on August 31, but not a ballistic missile alleged by the
United States, Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we cannot confirm that they have successfully launched
a satellite," Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, Space Command has not observed any object orbiting
the earth that correlates with the orbit announced by the North
Koreans in their public statements," Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Bacon said the intelligence analysis could take some time and
"it would be premature to make firm statements about the exact
equipment that was used and the exact purpose of the launch or the
degree of success that they realized in their launch at this
state." 
</P>
