<HEADLINE> Thailand to Auction Huge Assets of Closed Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Financial Sector
Restructuring Authority (FRA) has announced that the largest
auction of core assets of 56 closed finance firms, worth billions
of U.S. dollars, would take place on December 2.
</P>
<P>
The auction of the assets, estimated at 460 billion baht (11.5
billion U.S. dollars), would not only be the largest in Thai
history, but also in the world, FRA chairman Amaret Sila-on was
quoted by Wednesday's Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sale of the core assets would mean that more than 90
percent of the total assets of the closed firms would be sold and
the rest would be gradually sold before the year's end, Amaret
said.
</P>
<P>
The asset sale comprises 2,000 business loans from all 56
closed firms. Lehman Brothers is serving as financial adviser to
FRA for the sale.
</P>
<P>
The auction of business loans follows the successful completion
of sales of hire purchases contracts and residential mortgages by
the FRA.
</P>
<P>
The business loan portfolio alone contains more than 50 percent
of the total assets of the finance companies when they were
suspended last year.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary sales information, including bidding procedures,
will be available on the FRA Web site (www.fra.or.th) or at FRA
office building from next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The FRA has to complete its mission of selling assets of the 56
closed firms this year, as instructed by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government closed the 56 debt-ridden firms late last
year in a major step to streamline the trouble-stricken financial
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
