<HEADLINE> Mexican President Urges Fiscal Discipline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Tight fiscal discipline is
essential in the Mexican banking system if the country is to fend
off international financial turbulence, Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Discipline was needed to consolidate the financial, fiscal and
structural strengths of the economy in the long term, the
president said at a ceremony for certified public accountants.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo also said that it was important for economic sectors
and political forces to act with the highest responsibility and
patriotism in order to promote the necessary unity to enter the
year 2000 with a stronger and better prepared nation.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's participation in international trade had been one of
the pillars with which Mexico had overcome 1995's economic crisis,
Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
Whenever the international financial system became highly
unstable, Mexico's achievements were put to test.
</P>
<P>
"Towards external instability, we'll maintain internal
strength. Thus we will come out well from the current
international situation," the president said. 
</P>
