<HEADLINE> Thai Senior Officials to Drive Less Powerful Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet has approved
a proposal by the permanent secretary of the Prime Minister's
Office on limiting the engine capacity of motor vehicles for
high-ranking officials, a government press release available
Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
The Budget Bureau suggested that the engine capacity of the
prime minister's car and those of deputy prime ministers does not
exceed 3,000 c.c.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also suggested a reduction of price for the prime
minister's and his deputies' cars.
</P>
<P>
For cars of the officials of other committees and independent
agencies, their capacity will be decided on the basis of the
officials' salary, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cabinet has revoked a regulation which allowed
government agencies to buy cars confiscated by the Custom
Department.
</P>
<P>
This policy aimed to raise the savings of the government in the
current economic crisis, the press release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
