<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flourishing Silk Trade on Silk Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 9 (Xinhua) --Silk trade is still flourishing
on the world-famous ancient Silk Road. However, today this is
different story.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 years ago, camel caravans carried China's silk
and other goods along the Silk Road to central and western Asian
and European countries.
</P>
<P>
Today, trucks transport silkworm cocoons and raw silk produced
in the republics of Uzbekistan and Kyrghyz into China through
Kashi, an ancient Silk Road city in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, and the silkworm cocoons and raw silk are
later sent to the cities of Suzhou and Hangzhou, two major silk
producers in east China.
</P>
<P>
The old road was more than 7,000 kilometers long, began in
Chang'an (now Xi'an, capital city of northwest China's Shaanxi
Province), the ancient capital of the Western Han Dynasty
(B.C. 206-24), passed along the Gansu Corridor, and the Tarim
Basin in Xinjiang, ran through Uzbekistan, Turkmenia, Afghanistan,
Iran and Iraq, and ended at the sea ports of the Mediterranean in
Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Guli Bahan, a leading official of the Kashi Prefectural Foreign
Trade Bureau, called this modern-day "flow-backwards" on the
ancient Silk Road a new phenomenon resulting from China's
implementation of reform and opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The silk trade is assuming a leading position in commerce
between China and central Asian countries. Among Kashi's imports
from Uzbekistan and Kyrghyzstan, some 50 percent are natural silk
which is then transported to Suzhou and Hangzhou for further
processing.
</P>
<P>
Guli Bahan said that many central and western Asian countries
have mastered mulberry planting and silkworm raising, especially
Uzbekistan and Kyrghyz. But these countries are still lacking in
processing techniques.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, with the rapid economic development in the
Suzhou and Hangzhou areas, silk processing and cloth manufacturing
have became major industries, replacing the traditional mulberry
planting and raising of silkworms, so they require more raw
materials, Guli Bahan said.
</P>
<P>
The Turugart Pass on China's western frontier, bounded by the
Republic of Kyrghyz, has become a new and important trading center
along the Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
In the January-July period this year, the pass has handled
2,540 tons of silkworm cocoons and raw silk, valued at 2.03
million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government Unveils Overhaul of Tax System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has
introduced a new land tax system in a bid to boost annual revenue
and enhance land efficiency, according to a press release
available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The system, which would provide a legal basis for revamping the
current land tax structure, was sponsored by the Finance Ministry
and approved by the cabinet late Tuesday and would be tabled in
the parliament in its current session.
</P>
<P>
Akapol Sorasuchart, the government spokesman, said the system
provides for progressive tax rates on land left unused and
empowers local administrations to collect land and building tax in
areas under their jurisdiction for their own use.
</P>
<P>
Five tax structures, each with three tax rates, would be
introduced under the bill. Rates vary according to stages of
development of respective areas which are set as mostly,
moderately and least developed.
</P>
<P>
The first structure would be applied in Bangkok. In mostly
developed zones, the rates would be 0.095 percent of estimated
land prices, 0.075 percent in moderately developed zones and 0.055
percent in least developed zones.
</P>
<P>
The second, third, fourth and fifth structures would apply
outside Bangkok. Land in mostly developed zones would be charged
at between 0.045 and 0.08 percent of estimated prices, 0.035 and
0.065 percent in moderately developed zones and 0.025 and 0.05
percent in least developed zones.
</P>
<P>
Local administration bodies could use only one of the four
structures applied to areas outside Bangkok. Representatives of
state agencies concerned in each area would jointly decide which
structure to go for.
</P>
<P>
On enactment, the 1932 Household and Land Taxes Act, the 1965
Land Development Act and the 1986 Land Median Prices Act would be
abolished.
</P>
<P>
Akapol said taxes would be calculated on the estimated prices
of vacant land and the combined value of land and buildings on it
without reductions for depreciation.
</P>
<P>
He said vacant plots which are not exploited would be subject
to progressive tax rates. If the land left unused is for
residential purposes, the rates would double every three years. As
for land considered suitable for agriculture, the rates would
double every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
