<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, Greece, Romania to Enhance Police Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministers of
Bulgaria, Greece and Romania Tuesday signed a protocol on
enhancement of police cooperation to fight organized
international crime, according to the Bulgarska Telegrafna
Agentsia.
</P>
<P>
Under the trilateral agreement, police will make concerted
efforts in fighting a broad range of organized international crime
such as drug trafficking, illegal immigration, money laundering
and illegal financial transactions, Bulgarian Interior Minister
Bogomil Bonev said after the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The three sides will also exchange information on police work,
statistical data and crime forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Greece is expected to help its two partners introduce border
control systems in line with Schengen standards.
</P>
<P>
The pact also provides that the three countries' ministers in
charge of security shall meet once a year.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the need for the pact, Romanian Interior Minister
Gavril Dejeu said that organized crime has taken on most
clandestine forms that are very hard to control and is no longer
of concern solely to individual states but to the whole world.
</P>
<P>
The three countries also want to initiate a policy on security
in the Balkans and project a new image before the international
community and the rest of Europe, the Romanian minister said.
</P>
<P>
Greek Interior Minister Georgios Romeos said internal security
is an important precondition for a country's political stability
and social development.
</P>
<P>
The document has been approved by the three governments and
will be submitted for ratification by their respective parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The Greek island of Kerkira will host a meeting of interior
ministers from the Black Sea Economic Cooperation Organization,
where participants are expected to sign more agreements on
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The interior ministers of Greece and Romania arrived here
Monday on a three-day visit. This is a follow-up to the March
interior ministerial meeting in Thessaloniki, Greece, which ended
with a declaration on interaction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
