<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Congress to Increase Budget for Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday urged Congress to spend 5 billion U.S. dollars to support
the nation's public schools that have a record enrollment of 52.7
million children this fall.
</P>
<P>
"Let's get people out of the house trailers and get them out of
the falling-down buildings and give our kids something to be proud
of," Clinton said at Silver Spring, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
Because of the impact from the Baby Boom, 500,000 more children
will enter public and private schools in the United States this
year. College enrollment will also jump by 240,000 students, to
nearly 14.6 million.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that all the indications show that the
increase of enrollment will continue for years to come. Because
of the hike, schools are facing serious shortages in teachers and
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
After the peak Baby Boom years of the late 1950s and early
1960s, births fell sharply. As a result, classrooms were
underused and school buildings across the nation closed.
</P>
<P>
The president requested budget from February to provide 5
billion dollars over five years in building and repairing 5,000
schools.
</P>
<P>
He also called for funds to help school districts hire another
100,000 teachers to lower the class size, averaging 18 students in
the early grades. And he proposed to provide scholarships to
35,000 young people who will agree to go out and teach in
educationally underserved areas.
</P>
<P>
"This ought to be an issue where we can all say that it's a
national priority," Clinton said. "There is no more important
long-term objective for America than world-class education for all
our children," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
fanned out to other schools in observation of the administration's
"School Modernization Day."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said about 40 members of Congress and the Cabinet were
out all across the nation on Tuesday to campaign for education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
