<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Internet Server Market to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide Internet
server market will grow considerably as more users look to
purchase full-featured servers, rather than upgrade their current
systems with Internet software, according to a U.S. market
analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest, an information technology advisory service company
based in California, released a new study Tuesday, predicting that
revenue of the worldwide Internet server market will reach 13.27
billion U.S. dollars in 1998, up 114 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The market grew 276 percent in 1997, with revenue reaching 6.21
billion dollars, Dataquest said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the worldwide Internet server market was led by the
Silicon Valley company Sun Microsystems, whose revenue accounted
for 22.3 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
"It's important to remember that the Internet server market is
still in its infancy and has the kind of dynamic qualities that
promise not just change, but very quick change," Dataquest said in
a report. "As a result, significant opportunities exist for
vendors that do not currently in the upper reaches of the revenue
and shipment picture."
</P>
<P>
Although the market was dominated by a relatively small number
of vendors, Dataquest analysts said it is not too late for vendors
to succeed in this thriving market.
</P>
<P>
Midrange servers accounted for more than 63 percent of the
worldwide market in 1997, with revenue reaching 3.97 billion
dollars. Dataquest predicted that midrange Internet servers will
continue to dominate the market through 2002.
</P>
<P>
Midgrange systems are often found in such applications as
Internet database, Internet compute and high-end Internet file
serving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
