<HEADLINE> Ivanisevic Throws Racket in Frustration at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia
lost his temper and threw his racket in frustration during his
four-set loss to Patrick Rafter of Australia in today's match at
the U.S. Open tennis championships.
</P>
<P>
"It was everything. I was a chance to get me back into the
match. I hit a couple of good returns in the fourth set, and that
was the chance," said the 14th seed. "Then I came up with three
bad returns, and then I got the penalty point."
</P>
<P>
Rafter continually frustrated Ivanisevic in the fourth set,
causing the Coatian to fling his racket, which just missed a
ballboy.
</P>
<P>
Rafter, third seed and defending champion, enter the
quarterfinals but faced tougher fights than last year.
</P>
<P>
"I came into 1997 and I had a tough draw. I'd done really well
the couple of weeks before and I was 14th in the world. Now this
year, I came in with a good attitude again. I've learned to deal
with the pressures. I just came to this tournament and whatever
happens, happens."
</P>
<P>
Rafter will face Sweden's Jonas Bjorkman in the quarterfinals.
"Obviously I'm going to serve and volley. We've played each other
a lot. He knows my game inside out. I know his game pretty well.
It's going to come down to who can exploit weaknesses better that
day," said Rafter. 
</P>
