<HEADLINE> Brazil Announces 3.6 Billion Dollars Budget Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Brazil announced Tuesday a
budget cut of 3.6 billion U.S. dollars for the 1998 fiscal year
and new measures to deal with the consequences of the current
international financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The cut will mainly affect ministerial activities and
investment in public projects, Treasury Minister Pedro Malan said.
</P>
<P>
He said the cut should help produce a budget surplus of 4.2
billion dollars, up from the level of 3.64 billion dollars
previously expected.
</P>
<P>
The measures include plans to create a fiscal management
council, composed of members from the Treasury and Planning
Ministries, that will work to ensure the achievement of fiscal
goals.
</P>
<P>
The measures are aimed to tranquilize Brazil's financial market
before the international financial turbulence.
</P>
<P>
Malan added that the Brazilian government will encourage
internal savings and adopt a series of steps to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's international reserves fell to 58 billion dollars from
74 billion dollars, an alarming level to the national financial
situation. 
</P>
