<HEADLINE> Brazil's Trade Deficit With Mercosur Countries Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's trade deficit
with other Southern Cone Common Market (Mercosur) members went
down during the first half of this year, press reports said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's total trade deficit with Argentina, Uruguay and
Paraguay dropped by 70 percent, from 621.7 million U.S. dollars
between January and July last year to 217.9 million dollars during
the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of 1998, Brazil's trade deficit
with Argentina went down from 963 million dollars to 608 million
dollars, as a result of the country's 3.63 percent year-on-year
export increase, from last year's 3.56 billion dollars to 4.82
billion dollars, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of 1998, Brazil had a trade surplus of
500 million dollars with Paraguay, 70 million dollars more than
that of the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Total trade volume between Brazil and its three Mercosur
partners between January and July increased by more than 6
percent, from 10.24 billion dollars of the same period of 1997 to
10.86 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, established in December 1994 to promote free trade in
the region, is the biggest commercial bloc in South America. It
consists of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay. Chile and
Bolivia are its associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Turns Down Clinton Lawyer's Request for Report Preview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Independent counsel Kenneth
Starr Tuesday told U.S. President Bill Clinton's lawyer he opposed
letting him see the report in advance.
</P>
<P>
"You are mistaken in your views as to ... your right to review
a report before it is transmitted to Congress," Starr wrote
presidential attorney David Kendall.
</P>
<P>
Starr, responding to Kendall's letter Monday asking for access
to the report a week early, wrote, "I suggest you address your
concerns to the House of Representatives" after any report is
delivered under seal there.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's attorneys are concerned that Starr's report will be
one-sided and include extensive conclusions and legal analysis
instead of simply a listing of facts gathered in the seven-month
investigation.
</P>
<P>
"Elemental fairness dictates that we be allowed to respond to
any 'report' you send to the House simultaneously with its
transmission," Kendall wrote Starr.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority leader Trent Lott said there might have been
"more sympathy" for Kendall's argument if the White House had not
shown a pattern of belated disclosure on other congressional
investigations.
</P>
<P>
"Why is it fair that no one else in the world can get it, but
they can?" Lott said. "I really don't think presidents should be
entitled to this."
</P>
<P>
Lott made the comment after discussing the matter with House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, who is to go over the logistics of possible
hearings with Democratic leaders on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with other Democrats, Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle urged Clinton to elaborate on his recent apology, saying,
"I think that it's important that he continue to find appropriate
forums in which to add to the comment that he's already made."
</P>
<P>
Reaching out to lawmakers, Clinton invited House Democratic
leaders to the White House on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Lott, in reference to the arrival time of Starr's report, said,
"We don't know for sure."
</P>
<P>
House Republican leaders are still discussing procedural
issues, including how much authority, including the right to
subpoena, the House should grant the Judiciary Committee if senior
members decide enough evidence of impeachable offenses exists for
a full-blown inquiry after Starr's report is submitted.
</P>
<P>
In the House of Representatives, tensions are mounting over how
much of the report is to be made public and whether Democrats will
have a saying in the distribution and investigation of the
evidence it contains.
</P>
<P>
Gingrich and Minority Leader Richard Gephardt are scheduled to
talk for the first time Wednesday about the logistics of a
congressional investigation. Joining them will be Majority Leader
Dick Armey, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, who
would head any inquiry into Clinton's conduct and John Conyers of
Michigan, the panel's ranking Democrat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
