<HEADLINE> France, Egypt to Hold Meeting on Middle East Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- France and Egypt will hold a
talks here next Monday to prepare an international conference of
the countries seeking to "save the peace in the Middle East", the
French Foreign Ministry announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said, "This
meeting plans to fix the agenda of the peace conference initiated
in May by French and Egyptian Presidents (Jacques Chirac and
Hosni Mubarak)."
</P>
<P>
Chirac has said the conference, in calling together those
countries determined to save the peace in the Middle East, aims to
"confirm all the present achievements and define the conditions of
restarting the peace process".
</P>
<P>
The French-Egyptian initiative "is complementary to the
U.S. efforts for resuming the peace process" in the Middle
East, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to support the proposals made by the United States
in spring," she said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has proposed that Israel withdraw its troops from 13
percent of occupied territory in exchange for security guarantees
for Israeli and U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
Israel has reportedly rejected the French-Egyptian initiative
while the U.S. has expressed reservations about it. 
</P>
