<HEADLINE> Cyprus Defense Minister Criticizes Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cyprus Defense
Minister Yiannakis Omirou Tuesday criticized Turkey for its
expansionism, saying that it was a threat not only to Cyprus but
also to Greece.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on recent statements by Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz that Turkey would take all necessary measures if Cyprus
deployed Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, Omirou said on
the northwestern Greek island of Corfu that the present time was
critical for Cyprus' national issues, the semi-official Athens
News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said that the dangers of a destabilization in the eastern
Mediterranean region were real as long as the present situation of
division and occupation remained in Cyprus,
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Cyprus had the right and duty to defend
itself.
</P>
<P>
As for the violations of the Greek air space by Turkish fighter
jets in the Aegean Sea Tuesday, he said that this was the sort of
activity which indicated that neighboring Turkey did not want to
contribute to defusing the situation but in fact provoked and
attacked.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman emphasized that Greece was against the formation
of alliances and axes in the region and called for multilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Yilmaz's official visit to Israel, he said that
Greece welcomed assurances from Israel and Ankara that their
bilateral cooperation was not directed at any third party, but he
added that Athens retained its reservations until this was proved
in practice. 
</P>
