<HEADLINE> Canada Sends Helicopters to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada is sending three
helicopters and 50 troops to join the Canadian contingent already
in Bosnia helping restore stability and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Defense Minister Art Eggleton said Tuesday that the
CH-146 Griffins and troops will be deployed from 408 Squadron in
Edmonton, west of Canada. He said the helicopters will help
conduct reconnaissance, observation and transportation over an
area.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters are scheduled to be shipped by sea at the end
of September and will be based in Velika Kladusa. The patrols
will start in early November.
</P>
<P>
"The addition of the three helicopters will improve the
Canadian contingent commander's ability to conduct operations," he
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 Canadian troops have served in Bosnia and
Croatia with the United Nations and NATO since 1991. There are
about 1,250 Canadian Forces members in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Canada also has 130 personnel and six CF-18 fighter jets based
in Aviano, Italy. The jets are used to enforce the NATO no-fly
zone and have participated in peace exercises over Albania.
</P>
