<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto's Son-in-Law Questioned Over May Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former chief of the
Army's Strategic Reserves Command Prabowo Subianto Tuesday was
asked questions about the country's May riots which caused the
death of more than 1,000 people, national newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Fact-Finding Team investigating the May riots met
with Prabowo, son-in-law of former President Soeharto, to find out
what he knew about the country's worst outbreak of violence in
decades, Bambang W. Soeharto, who leads the team's subcommittee on
testimony, said.
</P>
<P>
The questioning took place at Prabowo's residence in Central
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"Prabowo welcomed us and (the questioning) lasted for about one
hour," Bambang said, adding that he was accompanied by team
members Bambang Widjojanto, who is a human rights activist, and
businesswoman Rosita S. Noer.
</P>
<P>
Bambang said Prabowo was questioned because he was chief of the
Army's Strategic Reserves Command when the riots broke out. His
troops were deployed on the streets of a number of Indonesian
cities.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo has denied allegations that he was behind the riots in
which thousands of shops and buildings were looted, damaged and
burned, Bambang said.
</P>
<P>
"There are rumors that I was behind the riots... that's not
true," Prabowo was quoted by Bambang as saying.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Defense and Security and Armed Forces Chief General
Wiranto has previously admitted that members of the military were
involved in the looting and burning. Many pundits suspected
Prabowo was behind the riots.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto discharged Prabowo from the military last month for his
involvement in the abduction and torture of political activists.
</P>
<P>
The government established in July the Joint Fact-Finding Team
which includes representatives of the Armed Forces, government
agencies, the National Commission on Human Rights and
non-governmental organizations to investigate reports that the
riots were masterminded.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo is the fifth prominent government official questioned
by the team, following former Jakarta Regional Military Commander
Major General Sjafrie, Jakarta's Governor Sutiyoso, former Jakarta
Police Chief Major General Hamami Nata and Chief of the Armed
Forces' intelligence unit Major General Zacky Anwar Makarim.
</P>
<P>
The team's chairman, Marzuki Darusman, said the team would soon
question Marines Corps chief Major General Soeharto to collect
more information about the riots, during which security was
allegedly non-existent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
