<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Ousted By Kucera in U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Ninth seed Karol Kucera of
Slovakia spoiled Andre Agassi's chances of a quarterfinal
showdown with top seed Pete Sampras of the United States as he
held off the eighth seed American in five sets today at the U.S.
Open tennis championships.
</P>
<P>
In a match that started Monday night and featured gamesmanship
by both players, Kucera completed a 6-3, 6-3, 6-7 (5-7), 1-6, 6-3
victory to earn a berth in the next round with Sampras, whom he
defeated in the quarterfinals at the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
Kucera came out strong today, holding at love in the fourth
game. After Agassi saved two break points in the next game to
hold serve, he broke Kucera to take a 5-1 lead, and held to force
the deciding set.
</P>
<P>
Agassi went up a break in the first game of the fifth set
after Kucera double-faulted on break point. But after Agassi held
serve,Kucera utilized brilliant shot-making to win the next five
games. Agassi held in the eighth game and missed a break point
opportunity in the next game.
</P>
<P>
Kucera forced match point in that ninth game on a running
forehand winner and prevailed when Agassi hit a backhand return
long.
</P>
<P>
Kucera seemed ready to close out Agassi on Monday night after
going up a break in the second game of the third set, but Agassi
fought back in the seventh game on a crosscourt backhand winner.
</P>
<P>
After some spirited gamesmanship between the two and a bizarre
lobbing strategy employed by Agassi in the ninth game, both
players held serve to force the tiebreaker. Agassi won the first
four points, lost the next five, then won the final three.
</P>
<P>
Overall, Kucera fired 18 aces and broke Agassi seven times to
overcome 65 unforceed errors. Agassi committed 81 unforced errors
as he lost in the fourth round for the second straight year at
the Open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
