<HEADLINE> Reports: Man United Accept Murdoch Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The board of Manchester United
is reported to have accepted an increased offer of 625 million
pounds (about 1.4 billion U.S. dollars) from BSkyB, the satellite
broadcaster controlled by Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
Sky Television News and The Times newspaper, both controlled
by the media magnate said the board of Britain's leading soccer
club accepted an offer of 240 pence a share, a total of 50
million pounds more than the satellite broadcaster's original bid.
</P>
<P>
The club is the largest in the United Kingdom in terms of
support and wealth. Its popularity has meant that it earns as
much from merchandise sales and advertising as from gate receipts.
</P>
<P>
The board stayed late on Monday night locked away in a London
business suite holding talks on Rupert Murdoch's bid, amid
opposition from fans and the likelihood of an Office of Fair
Trading investigation.
</P>
<P>
The club's share price soared on the UK stock market after
satellite television company BSkyB confirmed its interest on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Traders added more than 100m to the club's value, apparently
believing Murdoch would invest his millions in new talent for the
side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
