<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Postpone Activities of Some Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
considering postponing the activities of its embassies in some
countries for the sake of efficiency due to the uninterrupted
economic crisis, The Indonesian Observer reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The plan to postpone the activities of some embassies has been
suggested to the president, but there is no agreement yet,"
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas told a working meeting with the House
of Representatives here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Alatas explained that the government will declare "temporary
closure" for some embassies and will reopen those embassies when
the economic condition improves.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry will neither reduce the number of existing
embassies nor permanently close them, because it will take more
money to reopen them.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from that matter, the existence of our embassies is
needed to maintain and improve relations with other countries and
international organizations," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
For the sake of efficiency, he said, his ministry will also cut
the spending of Indonesian envoys in foreign countries. "And we
will keep our work running optimally," he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister emphasized that his office will continue reducing
the number of staff. "Reduction of the number of home staff and
local staff at our embassies will be continued in accordance with
the effort to improve human resources," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
