<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 00:30 GMT, September 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow industrials soared 380 points Tuesday,
setting its biggest point gain ever after the Federal Reserve
signaled it might lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average finished up 380.53 points at
8,020.78 -- the market's first returning above 8,000 points since
its 512-point drop on August 31. The blue-chip barometer gained 5
percent for the day.
</P>
<P>
However, the Dow is still sharply below its mid-summer peak.
The market is 1,300 points, or 14 percent, below its July 17
record of 9,337.97. (New York-Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton Tuesday called Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to discuss a wide range of issues,
White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
They would not describe what issues they discussed in their
telephone conversation. But reports said the two leaders discussed
Clinton's possible visit to South Asia, Asian economic problems,
India-Pakistan tension over the disputed Kashmir, and the
importance of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty. (US-Pakistan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- With campaign finance overhaul legislation being
resurrected in the U.S. Senate this week, Republican leaders say
they have the votes to kill it for good but supporters pledge a
strenuous fight.
</P>
<P>
Senators John McCain, a Republican, and Russell Feingold, a
Democrat, will offer their bipartisan bill as an amendment to a
fiscal 1999 Interior Department spending bill, McCain's office
said on Tuesday. (US-Campaign-Finance)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The Nigerian Defense Headquarters has warned of a
possible military confrontation at the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula,
which was both claimed by Nigeria and Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters said in a statement Tuesday in Lagos
that authorities in Yaounde last week deployed more troops to the
disputed areas along its border with Nigeria. (Nigeria-Cameroon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- A senior U.N. official said on Tuesday that
181 countries had entered their names for the general debate in
the upcoming 53rd session of the General Assembly (GA).
</P>
<P>
Jin Yongjian, under-secretary-general for General Assembly
affairs and conference services, told a press conference that 26
heads of state and 20 heads of government will take the floor in
the general debate, which is scheduled for September 21.
(UN-General Assembly)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States on Tuesday denied a report that
the U.S. military had detained an Iraqi vessel in the Gulf which
was carrying grain bought under an "oil-for-food" agreement with
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past weekend, 11 vessels were boarded (in the Gulf
region) and were cleared. None were detained," Pentagon spokesman
Marine Lt. Col. Pat Sivigny said. (US-Iraq-Vessel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Tuesday urged Iran and
Afghanistan to restrain themselves from taking any steps in
escalating tensions between them.
</P>
<P>
"We are urging restraint by all sides. We want Afghanistan's
neighbors to refrain from taking actions that could further
enlarge or inflame the conflict, and obviously, to respect its
international borders," State Department spokesman James Rubin
said at a regular briefing. (US-Iran-Afghanistan-Tension)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The Conference on Disarmament (CD) ended its 1998
session here Tuesday with no consensus on admitting Ecuador,
Ireland, Kazakhstan, Malaysia and Tunisia to the 61-member
conference.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of Morocco, Norway, Bangladesh, Algeria,
Sweden, Turkey, Ireland, Malaysia, Ecuador and Tunisia regretted
that the conference was not in a position to approve its expansion
although it was close to reaching a consensus and hoped this
decision could be taken at the start of its 1999 session.
(Disarmament Conference)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Visiting Cyprus President Yiannakis Omirou Tuesday
criticized Turkey for its expansionism, saying that it was a
threat not only to Cyprus but also to Greece.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on recent statements by Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz that Turkey would take all necessary measures if Cyprus
deployed Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, Omirou said on
the northwestern Greek island of Corfu that the present time was
critical for Cyprus' national issues, the semi-official Athens
News Agency (ANA) reported. (Greece-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Tuesday rejected a call from
the chief defense lawyer for two Libyan suspects in the 1988
Lockerbie airline bombing to negotiate a plan for the trial of
them in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that this was
a "nonnegotiable offer." (US-Libya-Trial) 
</P>
