<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Finding: Ancient Village Arranged in Celestial Pattern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 9 (Xinhua) -- The people of Yuyuan Village,
in east China's Zhejiang Province, have been told that the
buildings left by their ancestors were designed in accordance with
the positions of stars in the sky.
</P>
<P>
The small village in Wuyi County is surrounded by mountains,
and there is an S-shaped stream flowing through. Researchers
recently found that the stream was a man-made one, making the area
look like a Daoist talisman.
</P>
<P>
In the village there are 395 old buildings, which were placed
in positions corresponding to the 28 heavenly constellations.
</P>
<P>
There are seven ponds which were dug up for fire control and
drought relief. They are arranged in the shape of the Dipper, and
inside is located the village's ancestral hall.
</P>
<P>
Researchers discovered in the local archives that the village
was designed by Liu Bowen, a Daoist who was good at fortune
telling and helped Zhu Yuanzhang found the Ming Dynasty
(1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
"Such a design is aimed at praying to the gods to ward off
calamities and send blessings," the researchers explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980909.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada Strike Talks Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Six days after launching a
national strike, Air Canada pilots sat down with the airline
Tuesday to resume contract negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Marc Belanger, chairman of the Air Canada Pilots
Association, said the union's team of negotiators was "willing to
work around the clock" to get a fair settlement.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada had no comment on the resumption of negotiations
with the 2,100-member union.
</P>
<P>
The pilots are seeking a 12-percent raise spread over two years
to their current average salary of 100,000 Canadian dollars
(57,000 U.S. dollars) a year. The company's latest offer was a
boost of nine per cent over two years.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada, which normally carries 60,000 passengers daily, has
said flights would not resume until after an agreement is ratified
by the pilots' association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
