<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls on Possible Rate Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell Tuesday
against most major currencies on the pessimism about the
possibility that the Federal Reserve will lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The dollar slipped to a four-month low against the Japanese yen
and a nearly 10-month low against the German mark. The Mexican
peso fell to another historic low against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar dropped to 132.10 yen,
down from 133.57 yen late Friday. During trading, the dollar fell
as low as 131.20 yen, a level not seen since late April.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency also declined to 1.7285 marks, down from
1.7304. During the trading day, the dollar fell to 1.7230 marks, a
level last seen in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
In Mexico City, the dollar rose to a record 10.2700 pesos, up
from 10.2600 pesos Monday. In late trading in New York, the dollar
rose to 10.2400 pesos, up from 10.2100 pesos Friday.
</P>
<P>
Global stock markets rebounded after Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan Friday night hinted that the Fed is considering
lowering rates to fight the international economic illness.
</P>
<P>
While the Dow Jones industrial average soared 380 points
Tuesday following the three-day holiday weekend, U.S. Treasury
bonds and dollars fell. Traders believed that lower rates would
make bonds and dollars less attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Traders also were worried that the economic problems of Asia
and Russia would hit Latin America, causing the United States to
bail out its trading partners as it did with Mexico in 1994-95.
The peso fell to another low while Mexican equities rallied behind
the Dow Jones industrials.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday:
1.4142 Swiss francs, down from 1.4237; 5.7950 French francs, down
from 5.8029; 1,706.35 Italian lire, down from 1,708.00; and 1.5218
Canadian dollars, up from 1.5215.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6548 U.S. dollars, down from
1.6722 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
