<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian President Pleads for Admission to TRACECA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 8 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu Tuesday evening returned from Baku, capital of
Azerbaijan, where he attended the international conference on the
"Rebirth of the Historic Silk Road" alongside with representatives
from 31 countries and 13 international organizations.
</P>
<P>
President Constantinescu had pleaded for Romania at the Baku
conference, saying that his country wants to and can become a
turntable through the TRACECA (Transport Corridor
Europe-Caucasus-Asia) project due to its important crossing
position.
</P>
<P>
The president reminded among other advantages offered by
Romania its adequate infrastructure that is already available.
Thus, the Constanta harbor is the largest of the Black Sea's ones,
with a capacity of about 120 million tons freight a year, and
hosting oil ships of over 180,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"Romania also availed of a refining capacity of over 30 million
tons, with all its refineries being linked through conducts to the
Constanta port," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the national Rompres news agency, the two-day
International Conference on "Rebirth of the Historical Silk Road"
Tuesday ended in Baku after the signing of the Baku Statement and
the basic Multilateral Agreement on Europe-Caucasus-Asia
Transport.
</P>
<P>
The conference initiated by the presidents of Azerbaijan and
Georgia is trying to prove that the reconstruction of the old silk
way is the most direct and advantageous way for the circulation of
goods from Asia to Europe, as well as for the oil from the
Caucasus to Western Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
