<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate to Fight over Campaign Finance Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- With campaign finance
overhaul legislation being resurrected in the U.S. Senate this
week, Republican leaders say they have the votes to kill it for
good but supporters pledge a strenuous fight.
</P>
<P>
Senators John McCain, a Republican, and Russell Feingold, a
Democrat, will offer their bipartisan bill as an amendment to a
fiscal 1999 Interior Department spending bill, McCain's office
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A vote on whether to allow such an amendment to proceed to a
final vote, which requires the support of 60 senators, is expected
to occur Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In February, supporters of the bill failed to get 60 votes
needed to cut off debate. But it was given new life a month ago
when a companion bill in the House of Representatives, sponsored
by Representatives Christopher Shays, a Republican, and Marty
Meehan, a Democrat, overcame considerable odds and passed.
</P>
<P>
Both bills ban "soft money" -- unlimited and unregulated
donations to political parties -- regulate issue ads that purport
to educate voters but are actually often used to influence
elections, and expand disclosure requirements. Opponents consider
the legislation an assault on free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
Senate Republican Leader Trent Lott said Sunday that McCain
promised in February that he wouldn't try to revive the issue this
year, but now claims that the House vote changed the situation and
another vote was warranted. "I think that under the circumstances,
we should do that," Lott said.
</P>
<P>
But Lott, who opposes the legislation, said he didn't think
McCain had the votes to move the bill to passage.
</P>
<P>
Senator Mitch McConnell, who chairs the Senate Republicans'
money-raising effort and leads the opposition to McCain-Feingold
bill, said that with this week's vote, "we are hoping to
demonstrate that there has been no movement since February."
</P>
<P>
In February, all 45 Democrats and seven Republicans voted to
end the filibuster and move to a final vote. While well short of
the 60 needed to do that, supporters said that showed they have a
majority for passage.
</P>
<P>
Senator Carl Levin, a Democrat and a leading McCain-Feingold
advocate, said he is pushing for a more hard-line strategy in
which supporters refuse to give in even if they fail to get 60
votes.
</P>
<P>
Levin said that as long as they have 50 votes to keep an
amendment on the floor, floor managers must either continue debate
or pull the bill, something that's not feasible on a spending bill
that must be passed before the fiscal year begins October 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
