<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Pakistani Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 8 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
Tuesday called Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to discuss a
wide range of issues, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
They would not describe what issues they discussed in their
telephone conversation. But reports said the two leaders discussed
Clinton's possible visit to South Asia, Asian economic problems,
India-Pakistan tension over the disputed Kashmir, and the
importance of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Clinton originally planned to visit India and Pakistan in
November, but the plan was put on hold after the two countries
conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters that a
possible Clinton visit to the two countries was "still under
review." 
</P>
</TEXT>
