<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Roars Back on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 8 (Xinhua) -- The Dow industrials soared
380 points Tuesday, setting its biggest point gain ever after the
Federal Reserve signaled it might lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average finished up 380.53 points at
8,020.78 -- the market's first returning above 8,000 points since
its 512-point drop on August 31. The blue-chip barometer gained 5
percent for the day.
</P>
<P>
However, the Dow is still sharply below its mid-summer peak.
The market is 1,300 points, or 14 percent, below its July 17
record of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
The buying frenzy followed comments Friday evening by Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan indicating that the financial
turmoil in Asia and Russia may pose more of a threat than
inflation.
</P>
<P>
With the fiscal trouble abroad now threatening Latin America
and Canada, Greenspan said the Fed is becoming more concerned
about the world crises' drag on the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 was up 42.85 at 1,016.74, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite jumped 81.63 points at 1,648.15.
</P>
<P>
Advancers beat decliners by more than a 4-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 810.57 million
shares, compared with 777.65 million shares Friday.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index was up 22.28 at 508.59, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 22.02 at 624.73.
</P>
</TEXT>
